column168: NW 171084 NOTED WITH CONTENTS LEAKING FROM BOTTOM OF CAR BY LOCAL GOVERNMENT OFFICIALS AS TRAIN 124 PASSED THROUGH THEIR JURISDICTION. THE TRAIN WAS STOPPED AND INSPECTED BY THE CREW WITH COVERED HOPPER CAR NW 171084 FOUND TO BE RELEASING AMMONIUM NITRATE FERTILIZER. INSPECTION REVEALED THE MATERIAL WAS LEAKING FROM THE PARTIALLY OPEN BOTTOM SLIDE HOPPER DOOR.  THE DOOR WAS CLOSED AND PLUGGED BY CARRIER PERSONNEL STOPPING THE RELEASE. DOMERMOUTH ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CALLED TO CLEAN-UP SPILLED MATERIAL.

column168: RECEIVED RADIO CALL FROM CCT TRAIN CREW THAT RAIL CAR DRIPPING LIQUID IN TRACK 2. FOUND TANK GATX 18590 DRIPPING LIQUID. CALLED BNSF MECHANICAL DEPT SUPERVISOR & WAS ADVISED TO CHECKED TIGHTNESS OF BOTTOM VALVE. FOUND SEAL BROKEN ON TOP VALVE COVER HANDLE. REMOVE COVER HANDLE, INVERTED & PUT ON VALVE STEM. TIGHTENED VALVE ONE (1) FULL TURN & LEAK STOPPED. CAR THEN MOVED & SPOTTED ON ST SERVICES RAIL SPUR.

THIS SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN A BULK LOADED TRUCK WHEN IT ARRIVED AT THE MILWAUKEE RAMP. IT APPEARS HEAVIER FREIGHT SHIFTED DURING TRANSIT AND A HEAVY WOODEN  CRATE CRUSHED THE JERRICAN. SHIPMENT WAS A TOTAL LOSS. THE FREIGHT AND TRAILER WERE CLEANED BY TRAINED SPILL CLEAN-UP SPECIALISTS. REPORTS HAVE BEEN ISSUED TO TRUCK LOADING CREWS TO BE MORE AWARE OF LOADING HEAVY FREIGHT TO THE BOTTOM OF TRUCK LOADS TO PREVENT INCIDENTS SUCH AS THIS ONE.

THE BOX WAS SOAKED WHEN UNLOADING AND IT WAS STOPPED AND OPENED. THE PACKAGE INDICATED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS A PLANT GROWTH REGULATOR. THE PACKING SLIP THAT WAS FOLDED UP INSIDE A SMALL POUCH WAS TAKEN OUT AND IT IDENTIFIED THE PRODUCT AS THE ABOVE LISTED CORROSIVE. A MATERIAL DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED AND IT IDENTIFIED THE PRODUCT AS LISTED ABOVE AND INDICATES CORROSIVE. THE PACKAGE WAS DRUMMED AND HELD PENDING INVESTIGATION.
MAKING A HEATING OIL DELIVERY TO 1000 GAL TANK. VENT ALARM NOT WORKING PROPERLY-WHEN WHISTLE SHUT OFF OIL OUT THE VENT IMMEDIATELY.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: FORK LIFT IMPACTED THE 5 GAL PAIL DURING LOADING OPERATIONS IN THE BACK OF A TRAILER. THE RESULTING CREASE IN THE STEEL FORMED A PIN-HOLE LEAK THAT SPILLED APPROXIMATELY 1-2 OUNCES. SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED, THE DAMAGED DRUM PLACED IN SALVAGE DRUM AND SUFFICIENT COMPATABLE ABSORBENT WAS USED TO CUSHION AND ABSORB ANY FREE LIQUIDS. SAFETY MEETING SCHEDULED FOR 4/15/02 TO DISCUSS THE SPILL AND SMALL PACKAGE HANDLING PROCEDURES WITH ALL FACILITY STAFF.

PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING AT DOOR 113 ONE OF ONE ONE GALLON GLASS JAR THE DAMAGED CARTON WAS DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DISPOSAL PROCEDURE.

PACKAGE WAS TAKEN FROM PACKAGE TRUCK BY PART-TIME SUPERVISOR AARON JOHNSON, TO DAMAGE AREA AFTER PKG WAS PH TESTED AND LEAK WAS SOLIDIFIED AND CLEANED, BY MANAGEMENT RESPONDER JASON BROWN. THE PKG WAS PLACED I THE DAMAGE AREA NEAREST TO THE TSG CAGE. AT 9;:30 AM I ATTEMPTED TO PROCESS THE PKG. THE PKG APPEARED TO BE OK EXCEPT FOR SLIGHT LEAKING. BECAUSE IT WAS A HAZMAT, I DONNED PPE AND USED THE DECISION TREE AND THE HARMFUL: STOW AWAY FROM FOODSTUFFS RESPONSE SHEET. WHEN ATTEMPTING TO LIFT THE BOX BY SIDE HANDLES INTO A  SPILL TUB, THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX CAME UNDONE AND FOUR 4L GLASS JARS (48LBS) BROKE, SPILLING INTO A DRAIN AND OUT TOWARDS THE T.S.G CAGE AND DAMAGE AREA BOX SHELF. I IMMEDIATELY SPREAD CLAY BASED ABSORBENT OVER THE LARGE SPILL. AFTER CONTAINING THE SPILL I TOOK THE SOLIDIFIED SPILL AND PLACED INTO A LINED SPILL TUB AND BOX. SUPERVISOR JASON BROWN WAS THEN NOTIFIED. CESQG WAS THEN USED TO DISPOSE OF THE SOLIDIFIED SPILL PLANT ENGINEERING WAS NOTIFIED BECAUSE SPILL WAS OVER 2.2 LBS, A R.Q. AND SPILLED INTO DRAIN.

column168: XCL DSR WAS BREAKING THE TRAILER NOTICED THE FLOOR WAS SATURATED, NO SMELL. AFTER REMOVING HALF THE FREIGHT, HANDS STARTED BURNING IDENTIFIED THE PUNCTURED CORROSIVE PAIL.  PAIL WAS LOADED ON A SKID WITH NO PROTECTION UNDER PAIL AND NO BLOCKING.  APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN DAMAGED FROM THE PALLET IT WAS SHIPPED ON.
column172: Plastic pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: WHILE UNLOADING THE TRAILER WE FOUND 2 DRUMS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM BUNGS. WE PLACED THE TWO DRUMS IN OVERPACK DRUMS AND SENT THEM BACK TO THE SHIPPER.  THE QUART OF OF SPILLED FLUID AND THE CARDBOARD IT WAS ON WAS DISPOSED OF.
CARTON WAS KNOCKED OFF OF PALLET AND THE FORCE OF HITTING THE GROUND CAUSED A SMALL LEAK IN CONTAINER.  THIS CAUSED APPROXIMATELY 6 OZ'S TO LEAK.

DSR WAS WALKING INTO TRLR 441-5104 TO CK BEFORE UNLOADING.  NOTICED FLOOR WAS WET AND TOTE WAS LEAKING FROM VALVE AREA AND FROM TOP CAP.  TOTE WAS THEN TAKEN OUT OF TRLR AND PUT IN HAZ MAT BAY WITH PLENTY OF ABSORBENT AROUND IT TO CONTAIN SPILL
OPEN UP BACK OF TRAILER FREIGHT WAS ALREADY CRUSHED.  NO OTHER FREIGHT BY IT.  TOP OF ONE CAN CRUSHED, SMALL HOLE, VERY SMALL AMOUNT LEAKING.
column172: Can, other than metal or aluminum

column168: CYLINDERS LOADED ON TAIL OF TRAILER. A STRAP WAS USED TO SECURE FREIGHT FROM MOVING AROUND. THE STRAP THAT WAS USED RUBBER AGAINST THE NOZZLE, CAUSING THE CYLINDER TO OPEN.

column168: AT 10:00 AM ON 4-12-02 AN EMPLOYEE HAD JUST FILLED A NURSE TANK FROM THE STATIONERY TANK. AS HE WAS PULLING AWAY, THE FILL HOSE CAUGHT ON THE BACK OF THE NURSE TANK. THIS CAUSED A PIPE ON THE STATIONERY BULK TANK TO BREAK, CAUSING A SEVERE LEAK. HE IMMEDIATELY CALLED THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT AND THEY CAME AND SHUT OFF THE MAIN BELLY VALVE ON THE STATIONERY TANK. THIS COULD SIMPLY BE AVOIDED IN THE FUTURE IF THE EMPLOYEES WILL PUT THE FILLING HOSES BACK ON THE RACK WHEN FINISHED WITH THEM.

BOTH DRUMS ARE BEING HELD FOR DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED FIVE GALLON METAL PAIL WAS DISCOVERED ON THE DOCK. APPROXIMATELY HALF A QUART OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND DAMAGED PAIL WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTEEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: DRESSED IN FULL P.P.E. I ATTENDED A LEAKED AT DOOR #7 IN THE PRIMARY UNLOAD.  I FOUND A PACKAGE BEARING A DOT 5 PART LABEL AND A DOT DIAMOND PLACARD - FLAMMABLE LIQUID.  THERE WAS A NOTICEABLE STAIN ON THE TOP OF THE PACKAGE.  I CONSULTED THE DECISION TREE FOLLOWING ITS DIRECTION TO THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET.  UNDER THE RESPONSE SHEET GUIDANCE: THE SPILL WAS ISOLATED.  THE CONTAMINATED ITEMS WERE DISPOSED OF VIA THE DMN PROCEDURE.  THE UNCONTAMINATED ITEMS WERE RETURNED IN A SALVAGE DRUM, AND I DECONTAMINATED MY P.P.E.

PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED APPROXIMATELY 8:30 PM IN THE IRREGULARS, "HOLE", AREA ADVANCING DOWN THE BOTTOM OF THE CONVEYER BELT.  SMALL MOISTURE SPOT ON TOP OF BOX WAS NOTICED BY SUPERVISOR.  I WAS SUMMONED TO RESPOND.  WORE FULL PROTECTIVE GEAR AND USED PH TAPE.  TOOK BOX IN SPILL TRAY TO DMP AREA, WAS FOLLOWING DECISION TREE.  USED RESPONSE SHEET (CORROSIVE) TO PROPERLY PREPARE WASTE.

THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY REPORTED TO THE HUMAN DEVELOPMENT/RISK MANAGEMENT DEPARTMENT AT THE GENERAL OFFICE. I WAS INFORMED TO NEUTRALIZE THE CORROSIVE SPILL AND USE OIL-DRI FOR CLEAN UP. THE DAMAGED PRODUCT WAS REMOVED FROM THE REST OF THE SHIPMENT AND WAS PUT IN OS&D BAY.

I WAS CALLED TO THE 100 LINE AROUND 12:36PM TO RESPOND TO A PACKAGE WITH AN ORDER. WEARING MY PROPER.PPE I REMOVE THE TWO PACKAGES AND FOLLOWING MY DECISION TREE AND MY RESPONSE SHEET I TOOK THE PACKAGES BACK TO THE DMP CAGE. BOTH OF THE METAL CANS HAD LOOSE CAPS. (THEY WERE ALSO FOUND IN THE TRAILER LOADED ON THERE SIDES. THEY HAD ARROWS.) THE LIQUID WAS CONTAINED TO THE BOX. BECAUSE IT WAS A HAZARD AND THE CONTAINERS WERE COMPROMISED I HAD TO DMP ALL THE LIQUID CONTENTS. AFTER I DMP I PROPERLY DECONTAMINTED MY PPE.

WHEN BREAKING DOWN AN IMPORT ULD (PALLET) A STAFF (CONTRACT STAFF) NOTICED A LIQUID THAT HAD COME FROM A PIECE OF FREIGHT HAD SLIGHTLY SOILED HIS OUTER CLOTHING. THE LIQUID SMELLED LIKE JET FUEL. THE STAFF NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR AND THE SUPERVISOR NOTIFIED MYSELF. THE JET FUEL WAS ON THE STAFFS OUTER GARMENT, HE CHANGED CLOTHES AND SHOWERED. THE AREA WAS SEGREGATED. AWB AND INVOICE DID ALSO STATE DESCRIPTION AS "MEC"., AND MENTIONED A/C PARTS RETURNED FOR REPAIR, AND " CONTROL-ASSY GAS TURBINE FUEL". THE CONSIGNEE WOODWARD GOVERNOR WAS CONTACTED, THEY SAID THAT JET FUEL IS SOMETIMES STILL LEFT IN AIRCRAFT PARTS. SQ AT ORD WAS ADVISED, THEY ISSUED REPORTS TO SQ HEADQUARTERS, THE AIRPORT OF ORIGIN AND TRANSIT STATION. THE LOCAL FAA WAS ADVISED. THE FAA COLLECTED AS MUCH FUEL AS WAS LEFT (ABOUT 0.2L) AND THEY WILL CONDUCT FLASHPOINT TESTS. THE FAA ALSO SAID THAT JET FUEL LEFT IN A/C PARTS HAS BEEN A PROBLEM. THE FAA RELEASED THE A/C PARTS BACK TO US. WE PACKAGED AND HAD A HAZARD DISPOSAL COMPANY DISPO OF THE OLD PACKAGEING IN AGREEMENT WITH SQ.

DURING THE INSPECTION THE OFFICER GOT INTO THE BACK OF THE TRUCK AND DISCOVERED THAT 5 DRUMS OF CLASS 9 MATERIAL WERE LEAKING AROUND THE BUNGS CAPS AND WAS STANDING ON THE TOP OF THE DRUMS AS WELL AS BEING SPLASHED DOWN THE SIDES OF THE DRUM. THE ONYX DRIVER CALLED THE LOCAL OFFICE AND A CREW MOBILIZED TO THE REST AREA WHERE THE INSPECTION HAD TAKEN PLACE. THE DRIVER THEN USED ABSORBENT IN THE SPILL KIT THE PUT AROUND THE LEAKING DRUMS UNTIL THE SPILL CREW GOT THERE. UPON ON ARRIVAL THE 5  DRUMS WERE OVER PACKED AND THE REMAINING DRUMS WERE CHECKED TO MAKE SURE THERE WERE NO MORE LEAKING. DURING THIS INSPECTION SEVERAL OF THE NON-HAZARDOUS DRUMS WERE ALSO FOUND TO BE LEAKING AND WERE OVER PACKED ALSO. THE GENERATOR WAS NOTIFIED AND HE IS DOING HIS OWN INVESTIGATION INTO THE DRUMS QUALITY AND THE FOLLOWING OF PLANT PROTOCOL BY WORKERS. ONYX IS DEVELOPING A PLAN TO INSURE THAT EACH LOAD IS QC'ED PROPERLY BEFORE SHIPMENT OFF ANY GENERATORS SITE.

column168: FLEET ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES LLC WAS EN-ROUTE FROM THE FOUNDRY LOCATED AT 236 PROMENADE ST., PROVIDENCE, RI TO CWM CHEMICAL SERVICES LOCATED IN MODEL CITY, NY IN ORDER TO DELIVER A 30 YARD ROLL-OFF CONTAINER OF POLYCHLORINATED BIPHENYL CONTAMINATED SOIL FOR DISPOSAL.  DURING THE COURSE OF TRANSPORTATION, THE DRIVER STOPPED TO CONDUCT A ROUTINE TIRE AND LOAD CHECK AND NOTICED THAT A SMALL LEAK DEVELOPED AT THE REAR DOOR OF THE ROLL-OFF CAN.  AT THE TIME OF THE INSPECTION, THE DRIVER OBSERVED A SMALL AMOUNT OF CLEAR LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE REAR DOOR.  HE IMMEDIATELY PLACED A SHEET OF POLY UNDER THE DOOR TO COLLECT THE MATERIAL ESCAPING FROM THE PACKAGE.  IN ADDITION, HE USED AN ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO FURTHER CONTROL THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL.  THE DRIVER THEN CONTACTED FLEET'S SOUTH BOSTON SERVICE CENTER WHO, IN TURN, DISPATCHED NEEDED SUPPLIES & MANPOWER TO STOP THE LEAK, RE-SEAL THE REAR DOOR AND CLEAN-UP ALL MATERIAL RELEASED FROM THE CONTAINER.  UPON ARRIVING AT THE SITE, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT MOISTURE TRAPPED IN THE SOIL FORMED SMALL PUDDLES ON THE TOP OF THE LOAD, WHICH CAUSED FROM THE VIBRATION OF THE VEHICLE AS IT WAS IN MOTION THEREBY CAUSING THE MOISTURE TO SEPARATE FROM THE SOIL.  THE RESPONSE CREW ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUID WITH SPEEDI DRI, APPLIED A BEAD OF SILICONE GREASE TO THE REAR SEAL TO PREVENT ANY RESIDUAL MOISTURE FROM ESCAPING AND RE-SEALED THE CONTAINER.  IN ADDITION, ALL ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND SPILL DEBRIS WERE PLACED IN THE ROLL-OFF CAN AND WERE DISPOSED OF AT THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE, A SUITABLE LINER WILL BE USED FOR ANY SHIPMENT CONTAINING SOIL.  IN ADDITION, THE REAR SEAL WILL BE INSPECTED FOR DEFECTS AND REPLACED IF NEEDED.  A COMPATIBLE SEALANT (I.E. SILICONE GREASE) WILL ALSO BE APPLIED TO THE REAR SEAL TO PREVENT ANY MOISTURE FROM ESCAPING.

THE DRIVER THEN PROCEEDED TO LAY SOME ABSORBENT DOWN AROUND THE PAIL TO CONTAIN AND THEN PROCEEDED TO TIGHTEN THE CAP ON THE PAIL. AFTER FINISHING LOADING AT CUSTOMER DRIVER MADE SURE PAIL WOULD NOT LEAK ANYMORE AND PROCEEDED BACK TO THE TERMINAL. ONCE BACK AT THE TERMINAL PAIL WAS INSPECTED FURTHER BY A FOS AND WAS PUT IN OS&D WITH CARDBOARD APPLIED UNDERNEATH THE PAIL. THE DRIVER WAS INFORMED TO ALWAYS MAKE SURE WHEN PICKING UP HAZARDOUS MATERIAL OR ANY FREIGHT TO MAKE SURE CAPS ARE ALL SECURE BEFORE SIGNING ANY PAPERWORK OR LOADING ANY PRODUCT. WE WILL ENSURE WHEN WE PICKUP AT BORDEN CHEMICAL OR ANY OTHER PLACE OF BUSINESS TO ASK QUESTIONS REGARDING THE FREIGHT WE ARE PICKING UP SUCH AS ARE CAPS TIGHTENED PROPERLY. IS THE BILL PROPERLY FILLED OUT WITH THE APPROPRIATE INFORMATION AS FAR AS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ARE CONCERNED.

column168: 5 GAL PAIL PUT ON RAISED LIFT GATE. DRIVER'S HEEL KNOCKED OVER 5 GAL PAIL ONTO CEMENT IT FELL APPROXIMATELY 4 FEET

AT APPROXIMATELY 1630 HOURS ON 04/12/2002 A LEAK WAS DISCOVERED ON THE BOTTOM OF TANK CAR DOWX 6290 AROUND THE UNLOADING CONNECTION (PICTURE INCLUDE). THE TANK CAR WAS LOADED WITH SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION AND IT WAS SOLIDIFYING AS IT LEAKED OUT OF THE TANK AND COOLED. THE MAXIMUM DAILY LOSS CALCULATED ON A WARM DAY WAS LESS THAN ONE HALF GALLON PER 24 HOUR PERIOD, COOLER DAYS WOULD HAVE LESS LEAKAGE. THE TANK CAR ARRIVED AT THE SNOWFLAKE MILL THE EVENING OF 03/15/2002. THE APACHE RR DID NOT NOTICE ANYTHING WRONG WITH THE CAR BEFORE THEY TOOK CONTROL OF IT IN HOLBROOK PRIOR TO TRANSPORTING IT TO THE MILL. THE MILL WENT DOWN ON 03/22/2002 FOR AN OUTAGE AND DID NOT RESTART UNTIL 04/01/2002. THE LEAK WAS DISCOVERED WHEN THE OPERATOR WENT TO CONNECT TO THE TANK AND TRANSFER THE CONTENTS. THE TEMPORARY STORAGE SIDING WAS CHECKED AND THREE SMALL SPOTS WERE FOUND WHERE THE CAR MAY HAVE LEAKED. WOOD CHIPS AND THE TRACK BALLAST WERE REMOVED FROM THESE THREE SPOTS AND THE UNDERLYING SOIL PH CHECKED. THE PH OF ALL THREE SAMPLES WAS LESS THAN 7.5 INDICATING NO CONTAMINATION TO THE ENVIRONMENT. EMPTYING WAS COMPLETED EMPTY AT 1500 HOURS ON 04/19/2002 BASED ON AVAILABLE VOLUME IN THE ON-SITE CAUSTIC TANK. IT WAS DISCONNECTED AND WASHED WHILE STILL IN THE CEMENT LINED UNLOADING AREA. THE CAR WAS MOVED AND STORED TEMPORARILY UNTIL DIRECTIONS WERE RECEIVED FROM DOW THERE WAS NO INDICATION OF ANY LEAK AFTER THE CAR WAS UNLOADED AND WASHED. DOW DIRECTED THE MILL TO RETURN THE CAR TO THEIR FACILITY FOR INSPECTION AND REPAIRS. THE CAR WAS MOVED TO THE APACHE RAILWAY REPAIR SHOP ON 04/29/2002 TO BE PREPARED FOR SHIPMENT BACK TO DOW'S REPAIR FACILITY. THE APACHE RAILWAY HAS BEEN IN CONTACT WITH DOW FOR PROPER SHIPPING REQUIREMENTS. DUE TO THE DESIGN OF THE TANK CAR IT WAS NOT POSSIBLE TO DETERMINE THE NATURE OF THE DAMAGE OR THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK THIS INFORMATION WILL HAVE TO COME FROM THE DOW REPAIR FACILITY. THE TANK CAR WAS FULLY INSULATED WITH AN OUTER METAL JACKET. IT IS DESIGNED TO TRANSPORT SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION.

RESCAR INSPECTED THE MANWAY COVER GASKET, IT APPEARED TO BE OK BUT THEY REPLACED IT AS A PRECAUTION. THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE SECURED WRENCH TIGHT. THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

MR. DOUG FARRA WITH MINUTE MAIDE REPORTED THAT HIS WAREHOUSE SUPERVISOR DISCOVERED NATX 38495, LOAD ALCOHOLIC BEVERAGE, WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP WHILE SITTING ON A SIDE TRACK BEHIND THEIR FACILITY AT MCKEAN & DERBY STREETS IN AUBURNDALE, FL. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED TO CONTACT THE SHIPPER, MIDWEST GRAIN. CSXT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT CONTACTED THE CONSIGNEE, FLORIDA DISTILLERS, AND REQUESTED THEY RESPOND. MR BOB JOHNSON WITH FLORIDA DISTILLERS RESPONDED AND FOUND PRODUCT WAS FLOWING OUT OF THE LIQUID EDUCTION LINE ON TOP OF THE CAR. PRODUCT WAS FLOWING DOWN THE SIDES AND DRIPPING ONTO THE BALLAST BENEATH THE CAR. HE FOUND THAT THE LIQUID LINE VALVE WAS IN THE CLOSED POSITION AND THE PLUG WAS ONLY HAND TIGHT. HE TIGHTENED THE PLUG AND THE LEAK STOPPED. THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO THE CONSIGNEE'S FACILITY. INFORMATION WAS PROVIDED TO MR JOHN WOHLGEMUTH WITH MIDWEST GRAIN. HE WAS REQUESTED TO HAVE THE LIQUID VALVE INSPECTED WHEN THE CAR WAS RETURNED.

WAYCROSS TERMINAL MANAGEMENT REPORTED THAT A SWITCHING CREW HAD SMELLED A STRONG AMMONIA ODOR IN THE CLASSIFICATION YARD AND THAT THE CONDUCT WAS HAVING DIFFICULTY BREATHING. LOCAL FIRE DEPT. AND EMERGENCY MEDICAL WERE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED AND THEY RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. THE ENGINEER CONDUCTOR ON THE SWITCH CREW WERE TAKEN THE LOCAL HOSPITAL. THE ENGINEER WAS OBSERVED AND RELEASED WITHOUT TREATMENT, THE CONDUCTOR WAS KEPT FOR ADDITIONAL OBSERVATION AND TREATMENT. THE 11 TANK CARS THAT WERE IN THE VICINITY OF THE CREW WERE ISOLATED FOR INSPECTION. CSXT HAZMAT DIRECTOR MUR AND A CSXT RESPONSE CONTRACTOR INSPECTED THE CARS AND FOUND CAR GATX 47830 WITH THE "B" END LIQUID VALVE LEAKING VAPORS, THE ODOR WAS EVIDENT TOP OF THE CAR. THE VALVE WAS CLOSED 1/4 TURN AND THE PLUG WAS TIGHTENED 1 TURN, THE LEAK STOPPED. THE PRESSURE ON THE CAR WAS 100 PSIG. THE CAR WAS OBSERVED FOR 24 HOURS TO SEE IF ANY FURTHER RELEASE OCCURRED. THE WAS CAR RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION BY CSXT HAZMAT.

THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASE TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

OF CHARLOTTE, NORTH CAROLINA WAS CONTACTED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. ONE BAX GLOBAL INC. EMPLOYEE, WADE HAMPTON, AND ONE HAMBACHER EXPRESS EMPLOYEE, BILL GRIFFIN, WERE EXPOSED TO FREE PRODUCT. BOTH EMPLOYEES WASHED THEIR SKIN AND WENT TO CAROLINA MEDICAL CENTER IN CHARLOTTE, NC, WHERE THEY WERE TREATED AND RELEASED. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION OF THE TRAILER, THREE LEAKING 18.93 LITER STEEL PAILS WERE DISCOVERED ON A PALLET. APPROXIMATELY 37.85 LITERS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND CONTAINED TO THE ASPHALT YARD USING ABSORBENT PADS. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO THE PAILS BEING CRUSHED BY ADJACENT FREIGHT, DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFTING IN TRANSIT AS A RESULT OF IMPROPER LOADING. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS,FREE PRODUCT AND THREE LEAKING PAILS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, TWENTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL RECOVERY DRUM AND THREE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL RECOVERY DRUMS. THE CONTAMINATED PALLET WAS PLACED INTO ONE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL RECOVERY DRUM. ALL FIVE RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: TRAILER AT LOADING RACK LOADING ARM CAME OUT OF TRAILER PRODUCT SPILLED ALL OVER CUSTOMER CLEANED UP.

column42: AMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S. OR POLYAMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S.
column168: DRIVER DIRECTED TO FILL LINE HOOKED UP AND STARTED UNLOADING THE FILL LINE INSIDE BUILDING HAD BEEN DISCONNECTED. CUSTOMER HOSED INTO SUMP AREA.
DISCONNECTING HOSE AT THE PUMP AND DROPPED THE CAP. PICKING UP CAP AND LOST PRODUCT USED SPILL PADS TO CLEAN UP
BETZ REP TOOK CAP OFF FILL LINE AND PRODUCT CAME OUT CAP

THE DRIVER WAS TRYING TO GET A SAMPLE FROM THE REAR DISCHARGE VALVE INTO A 5 GALLON BUCKET. HE OPENED THE INTERNAL VALVE TO FILL THE DISCHARGE LINE, CLOSED INTERNAL AND REMOVED CAP FROM EXTERNAL VALVE, STARTED TO OPEN VALVE AND THE PRODUCT MISSED THE BUCKET AND STREAMED ONTO THE GROUND. DRIVER AND UNLOADING PERSONNEL SPREAD OIL DRY ON THE PRODUCT AND SCRAPED INTO 5 GALLON PAIL.

THE DRIVER AIRED-UP THE TRAILER TO UNLOAD THE CARGO TANK INTO THE CONSIGNEE'S STORAGE. THE PRODUCT STARTED TO LEAK FROM THE DOME. THE DRIVER SHUT OFF THE AIR SOURCE, CLOSED VALVES AND INSTALLED A NEW GASKET ON THE DOME OF THE CARGO TANK. UNLOADER WASHED DOWN THE AREA INTO THE WATER TREATMENT SYSTEM.

THE DRIVER WAS GOING THROUGH HIS UNLOADING PROCEDURE. HE WAS IN THE PROCESS OF HOOKING UP HIS VAPOR RETURN HOSE AND DISCHARGE HOSE.  THE CONSIGNEE UNLOADING SUPERVISOR HOOKED THE HOSE TO HIS FITTING AND THE DRIVER WAS REMOVING THE HOSE CAP END TO HOOK TO THE TRAILER. INVESTIGATION REVEALS THAT THE CONSIGNEE'S  UNLOADER OPENED THE VALVE ON THE DISCHARGE LINE CAUSING THE PRODUCT TO FILL HOSE. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, WET CARTON AND DAMAGED PAILS WERE PLACED INTO A TEN GALLON RECOVERY DRUM.  THE CASE OF SMOKING TOBACCO, PRO NUMBER 147-077439-8 WAS PLACED INTO A FIFTY-FIVE GALLON RECOVERY DRUM.  HE AFFECTED CARTONS OF PRO NUMBER 135-928983-8 WERE PLACED INTO A TEN GALLON RECOVERY DRUM. EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR (HMHTTC) WAS DISPATCHED AND OVERPACKED THE AFFECTED DRUM ALONG WITH PROVIDING DECONTAMINATION OF THE TRAILER FLOOR WITHOUT INCIDENT. NO WATERWAYS, STORM DRAINS OR GROUND (SOIL) SURFACES IMPACTED.

WHILE TRAVELING ACROSS THE DOCK, DOCKWORKER DISCOVERED SAID PAIL TEMPORARILY STAGED ON DOCK WITH A SLIGHT WET SPOT AROUND IT. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE PAIL HAD BEEN STRUCK BY ANOTHER PIECE OF FREIGHT WHILE STAGED ON DOCK. SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED WITH ABSORBENT AND DAMAGED PAIL WAS PLACED INTO A RECOVERY CONTAINER AWAITING FINAL DISPOSITION.

WHEN DELIVERY DRIVER ARRIVED AT A DELIVERY HE NOTICED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE BACK CORNER OF HIS TRAILER. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION HE DISCOVERED THAT HIS PALLET JACK THAT HE WAS CARRYING INSIDE HIS TRAILER HAD BROKEN LOOSE FROM IT'S SECUREMENT CHAIN AND HAD STRUCK AND PUNCTURED A DRUM. THE DRIVER LAID THE DRUM ON ITS' SIDE AND USED HIS VEHICLE SPILL KIT TO CONTAIN AND CLEAN UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL. THE HOLE IN THE DRUM WAS REPAIRED WITH PUTTY AND WAS PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AWAITING FINAL DISPOSITION.

WHEN UNLOADER FREIGHT FROM TRAILER, DOCKWORKER DISCOVERED A PAIL THAT WAS SLIGHTLY LEAKING FROM THE BUNG CLOSURE. NOTHING CONTRIBUTED TO THIS FAILURE OTHER THAN IT BEING A DEFECTIVE CLOSURE. PAIL WAS PLACED INTO A RECOVERY CONTAINER AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER AS PER INSTRUCTED.

column168: DRIVER WAS UNLOADING INTO AN 8,000 GALLON REGULAR TANK. HE STARTED WITH A STICK READING OF 20. ACCORDING TO THE TANK CHART PROVIDED BY EXXON THERE WAS ROOM FOR 6,261 GALLONS. THE DRIVER HAD 5,200 GALLONS LOADED. HE WAS A COUPLE OF MINUTES  INTO THE DELIVERY WHEN HE NOTICED GAS SPITTING OUT FROM BELOW THE REGULAR FITTING.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY STOPPED ALL PRODUCT FLOW THOUGH  THE DISCHARGE VALVE AND THE INTERNAL VALVE.  THE PRODUCT KEPT FLOWING FROM THE OVERFILL SYSTEM IN THE FILL. HE THEN REMOVED THE FITTING WHEN A GUSH OF GASOLINE CAME UP FROM THE FILL. THE DRIVER THEN STUCK HIS ARM INTO FILL PIPE TO TRY AND STOP SPILL. HE THEN CAPPED THE FILL WHICH STOPPED PRODUCT. THE MONTGOMERY COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD ARRIVED AT THIS TIME. THEY BEGAN THE RESPONSE WITH LAYING STAY DRY AND CONTAINING PRODUCT. IT WAS TO THEIR BELIEF THAT SOME OF THE GASOLINE ENTERED A STORM DRAIN INTO THE WATERWAYS.  AFTER MDE (MARYLAND DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENT) HAD FOLLOWED THE STREAM FOR A COUPLE OF MILES  IT  WAS CONCLUDED THAT THERE WAS NO TRACEABLE ODOR OF GASOLINE. . THE MDE,  FIRE DEPARTMENT AND HAZMAT RESPONSE ALL OBSERVED THE UNLOADING OF REMAINING PRODUCT LEFT IN COMPARTMENT AND CONCLUDED THAT THERE WAS A PROBLEM WITH THE STORAGE TANK OR THE VAPOR SYSTEM. ALL DELIVERIES WERE STOPPED AT LOCATION UNTIL FURTHER INVESTIGATION. THE FINAL ACCOUNT OF LOSS PRODUCT WAS ABOUT 140 GALLONS. WE HAD AN OBSERVATION ON 4/30/02 WITH EXXON, MCKENZIE AND MDE IT WAS FOUNDED THAT THE OVERFILL PROTECTION BALL FLOAT WAS STUCK IN THE VENT PIPE .   ON 4/29/02  THERE WERE MODIFICATIONS MADE PRIOR TO TESTING , EXXON HAD THEIR CONTRACTORS CROMPCO CORP. AND REPLACED THE PRESSURE RELEASE VALVE. AFTER TESTING, THE BALL FLOAT WAS REPLACED IN THE REGULAR AND PLUS TANKS ON 4/30/02.   ALL DELIVERIES WERE RESUMED BACK TO NORMAL ON 4/30/02

column168: OUR TRUCK WAS TRAVELING INTERSTATE 495 BETWEEN ROCKVILLE PIKE AND CONNECTICUT AVE. IN MONTGOMERY COUNTY, MARYLAND. THE DISCHARGE PIPING SNAPPED DUE TO A MISSING 'U' BOLT. THIS BOLT HELD THE PIPING AS IT WENT INTO THE TOP OF THE TRUCK. THIS IS A TOP DISCHARGE WITH A TUBE SET INTO THE TANK MUCH LIKE A STRAW IN A GLASS. THE LIQUID IS THEN PUSHED WITH PRESSURE UP THE TUBE AND OUT. THE PIPE BROKE IN TRANSIT AND THE DRIVER PULLED OVER TO THE SHOULDER WHEN HE REALIZED HE HAD A PROBLEM. ONCE THIS PIPE BROKE IT FORCED THE BLEACH OUT UNTIL THE PRESSURE WAS ZERO WHICH TOOK ABOUT TWO TO THREE MINUTES. WE ESTIMATE THE LOSS OF PRODUCT AT ABOUT 150 GALLONS. WE HAD ALL OF OUT TANK TRUCKS CONVERTED TO TOP DISCHARGE IN 1999 TO ELIMINATE LOOSING ALL OF THE CONTENTS IN THE EVENT OF A CATASTROPHE. BY HAVING A TOP DISCHARGE WE WILL ONLY LOOSE A SMALL AMOUNT VERSUS THE WHOLE LOAD.

ON DELIVERY FOR 4/1/02 HAD PUMP LEAK AND CALLED MANUFACTURER MISSISSIPPI TANK.  ON 4/3 TRACTOR & TRAILER WENT TO TERMINAL SERVICE, TALLAHASSEE, FL. TO GET CLEANED OUT.  ON 4/8 TRUCK WENT TO MISSISSIPPI TANK WHERE 3 LEAKS IN DIFFERENT PLACES FOUND AND THE PUMP WAS WORKING.  DID TAKE A FEW MINUTES FOR THE PUMP TO START WORKING.  PUMP MADE BY BLACKMER AND THEY STATED ONLY 2 THINGS COULD OF CAUSED THE LEAK 1) PRODUCT WAS NOT COMPATIBLE WITH THE SEALS 2) LINE WAS OVERPRESSURED UNLOADING.  MISSISSIPPI TANK REPLACED THE 2 SEALS AND INSTALLED A NEW BYPASS VALVE.

QT02/Q01 HAD THE 2 SEALS AND A NEW BYPASS VALVE INSTALLED IN THE BLACKMER PUMP ON 4/8-4/9 AND PUMP STARTED TO LEAK AGAIN ON 4/12.  THIS TIME MISSISSIPPI TANK AND BLACKMER UNDER NEGOTIATIONS ON WHY PUMP WAS LEAKING. PROBLEM WAS WITH SEALS.  THIS WAS DISCOVERED THROUGH TESTING AT LAB AND ON OTHER TRUCK QT01/Q02 PUMP ALSO HAD LEAK.  ON 4/29 TRUCK TAKEN TO TERMINAL SERVICE, TALLAHASSEE, FL AND PUMP GASKETS REPLACED.
HAD PROBLEM WITH BLACKMER PUMP AN QT02/Q01 AND NOW QTO1/Q02 WAS HAVING SAME PROBLEM. BLACKMER SENT REPLACEMENT GASKETS TO GRACE TRAILER, MEMPHIS, TN FOR REPAIR ON 4/29/02.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS DELIVERING TWO ANHYDROUS AMMONIA NURSE TANKS TO A CUSTOMER ON FULTON COUNTY HIGHWAY 26, WHICH IS A GRAVEL ROAD. APPROXIMATELY 2 MILES NORTH OF ELLISVILLE ILLINOIS, HE ENTERED A CURVE ON THE TOP OF A HILL, TRAVELING APPROXIMATELY 35 TO 40 MILES PER HOUR. AS HE WENT DOWN THE HILL HE APPLIED HIS BREAKS TO SLOW DOWN. AT THIS TIME THE REAR ANHYDROUS AMMONIA TANK BEGAN TO WHIP AROUND, PUSHING THE OTHER TANK PICKUP TRUCK TOWARD THE DITCH ON THE EAST SIDE OF THE ROAD. IN AN ATTEMPT TO CORRECT THE TRUCK AND AVOID GOING INTO THE DITCH, THE DRIVER ACCELERATED AND REGAINED CONTROL OF THE TRUCK. AT THIS TIME THE REAR TANK WAS SLIDING SIDEWAYS IN THE ROAD. THE TIRES ON THE TANK CAUGHT IN THE ROAD AND FLIPPED THE TANK, TEARING IT AWAY FROM THE TRAILER IT WAS MOUNTED ON, WHICH REMAINED ATTACHED TO THE FIRST TANK AND PICKUP TRUCK. THE TANK LANDED ON ITS TOP, BREAKING AWAY THE SAFETY CAGE, LIQUID WITHDRAWAL VALVE AND VAPOR VALVES.

column168: #1 WAS EASTBOUND ON HIGHWAY 41, EAST OF HIGHWAY 81, SOUTHEAST OF GENEVA, NE. THE HIGHWAY IN THIS AREA IS ASPHALT SURFACED. THIS AREA IS A RURAL FARM AREA. THE VISION WAS LIMITED FOR THE DRIVER BECAUSE OF HEAVY CLOUD COVER. THE DRIVER WAS TRAVELING AT THE SPEED LIMIT IS 55 MPH. IN THE LANE IN FRONT OF THE DRIVER WAS 1 BLACK ANGUS COW STANDING STILL. THE DRIVER COULD NOT AVOID HITTING THE COW. AFTER THE IMPACT WITH THE COW, THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF HIS VEHICLE BECAUSE OF A DAMAGED STEERING AXLE. THE UNIT ROLLED ONTO ITS LEFT SIDE THEN ROLLED INTO THE WESTBOUND GRADER DITCH. THE TRAILER SLID DOWN THE ROADWAY FOR OVER 100 FEET BEFORE ROLLING INTO THE GRADER DITCH. THE FRONT COMPARTMENT WAS SCRAPED OPEN BY THE ROADWAY SLIDE AND PUNCTURED BY AN OBJECT IN THE DITCH. APPROXIMATELY 800 GALLONS OF NO-LEAD GASOLINE WAS LOST IN THE DITCH.

THE DRIVER FAILED TO FOLLOW SAFETY PROCEDURES ON IMPLANT ACID MOVEMENT AT PHELPS DODGE MORENCI. THE VENT VALVE WAS LEFT OPEN ON THE TANKER WHEN THE DRIVER OFF-LOADED PREVIOUS LOAD. TANKER WAS NOT INSPECTED WHEN IT WAS LOADED, RESULTING IN AN ACID SPILL. THE INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO SECURITY AND ALL ACTIVITY WAS SHUT DOWN. B.J. CECIL EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED TO THE SPILL. THE SULFURIC ACID WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH AND WATER. THE DRIVER WAS TERMINATED THE SAME DAY AFTER DETERMINING THAT HE WAS RESPONSIBLE FOR THE SPILL AND NOT FOLLOWING SAFETY PROCEDURES.

AATCO TRUCKING HAD A TRACTOR HIT A SNOWPLOW IN A SNOW BLIZZARD. THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER WAS TORN AND A 1.1 FELL OUT. THE DRIVER AND SNOWPLOW DRIVER PICKED THE DYNAMITE UP AND SET IT ON SIDE OF THE HIGHWAY. AATCO CALLED PERTS WRECKER SERVICE OUT OF SHERIDAN, WY. THEY WILL BRING A DRY BOX VAN DOWN AND LOAD THE FREIGHT OUT OF THE DAMAGED VAN AND THE BOXES FROM THE SIDE OF THE HIGHWAY. THESE WILL BE CARRIED TO SHERIDAN. PERTS WRECKER SERVICE HAS REMOVED ALL OF THE BOX OF DYNAMITE.

THE ABSORBENT WAS DISPOSED AS A HAZARDOUS WASTE.

AFTER RELOADING CONTAINER WAS ALLOWED TO CONTINUE ON TO ORIGINAL DESTINATION. NO FURTHER CLEAN UP WAS NECESSARY IN CONNECTION WITH THIS INCIDENT.

DURING SWITCHING OPERATION A CPR EMPLOYEE REPORTED BEING SPLASHED BY A LIQUID COMING FROM GATX 2039, CAR WAS ISOLATED AND AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED TO INVESTIGATE THE CAUSE, TO MAKE REPAIRS, AND TO CLEAN UP SPILLED PRODUCT. THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS DETERMINED TO BE A BROKEN PIPE CONNECTING THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY TO THE TANK CAR. A REPLACEMENT VALVE WAS USED TO SECURE THE LEAK. ONCE THE LEAK WAS REPAIRED THE CAR WAS ALLOWED TO CONTINUE ON TO ORIGINAL DESTINATION.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: OUR TRUCK, A 3000 GALLON FUEL OIL TRUCK, WAS HEADED WESTBOUND ON STATE RD. IN UPPER PROVIDENCE TOWNSHIP.  THE TRUCK CAME INTO A TURN WHICH THE DRIVER COULD NOT NEGOTIATE.  THE OIL IN THE TANK SURGED AGAINST THE SIDE OF THE TRUCK CAUSING IT TO TURN OVER.  I RECEIVED A CALL AROUND 11:30 4/9/2 THAT ONE OF OUR TRUCKS HAD TURNED OVER.  THE CALLER TOLD ME THE TANK ON THE TRUCK HAD BEEN CRACKED AND OIL WAS LEAKING OUT.  I IMMEDIATELY CALLED J.J. SPILL IN. WHO ARRIVED ON THE SCENE WITHIN THE HOUR WITH A VACUM TRUCK.  I ALSO DISPATCHED ANOTHER OIL TRUCK TO THE SCENE TO PUMP OFF THE REMAINING OIL FROM THE TRUCK IN THE ACCIDENT.  I ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AROUND 40 OR 50 MINUTES AFTER THE INITIAL CALL.  SINCE THE ACCIDENT WE REINFORCE OUR COMPANY DRIVING POLICY AT OUR WEEKLY SAFETY MEETINGS.

column168: WHILE PUMPING OFF DIESEL INTO ABOVE-GROUND TANK, A DEFECTIVE VALVE ON CUSTOMERS TANK DID NOT OPEN UNDER PRESSURE, CAUSING THE DISCHARGE HOSE TO BUILD PRESSURE, AND CRACKED THE FITTING ON END OF HOSE. DRIVER WAS STANDING AT VALVE AND SHUT OFF IMMEDIATELY, CAUSING A LOSS OF APPROXIMATELY 160 GALLONS.  SAND-PILE AT SITE WAS USED TO CONTAIN SPILL. SAND WAS TESTED (AGUATIC TOXICITY SCREEN), AND WAS RELEASED BY LOCAL SAN JOAQUIN ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH, AND DISPOSED OF FORWARD INC. LOCAL LAND FILL (ATTACHED).  VALVE WAS REPLACED ON CUSTOMERS TANK AND WORKS FIND.

THEY RESPONDED, CLEANED THE TRAILER AND THE DRUMS AND SECURED THE LOAD TO MOVE ON.  THEY GENERATED NO WASTE. THERE IS SOME WATER ON THE TOP OF THE DRUMS FROM THE CLEANING PROCEDURE BUT ALL OF THE AMINES AND THE ODOR IS TAKEN CARE OF.  SPILL CLEANUP COMPLETE. AFTER THE INITIAL RESPONSE BY DLS, THERE WERE SEVERAL (63) MORE DRUMS THAT WERE FOUND TO BE LEAKING ONCE THE TRAILER REACHED ITS DESTINATION.  MALLARD ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTACTED TO TAKE CARE OF THIS PROBLEM.  THE SPILL(S) OCCURRED DUE TO IMPROPER TIGHTENING OF THE BUNGS BY THE SHIPPER.  THERE WAS ALSO ONE DRUM THAT HAD A HOLE RUBBED IN IT.  MALLARD DOES NOT BELIEVE THAT THIS HOLE WAS CAUSED BY TRANSIT.  IT LOOKS AS IF THE DRUM WAS SCOOTED AND WORN BEFORE OR DURING LOADING.  CLEANUP IS NOW COMPLETE, THE BUNGS ARE NOW TIGHT ON 89 DRUMS AND ONE DRUM IS IN AN OVER-PACK.  MALLARD GENERATED 1-2 DRUMS OF PPE AND ABSORBENT THAT THEY WILL BE DISPOSING OF.  DISPOSITION: HMONE RECEIVED A CALL FROM JIM ABOUT THE SPILL; HE IS CONCERNED ABOUT THE CLEANUP IN TEXAS.  THE PROPER AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED AND JIM IS WAITING ON A SPILL REPORT FROM DLS ON MONDAY

column168: THE INCIDENT TOOK PLACE AT THE LOAD-OUT PLATFORM USED TO REFILL AMMONIA NURSE TANKS. AN EMPLOYEE OF LANDMARK AGRONOMY SERVICES PULLED AWAY FROM THE LOAD-OUT PLATFORM WITH THE VAPOR AND LIQUID FILL HOSES STILL ATTACHED TO THE WAGON. THE VAPOR AND LIQUID FILL HOSES ARE ATTACHED TO THE SAFETY BREAKAWAY VALVE. THE LIQUID HOSE BROKE AWAY FROM THE BREAKAWAY VALVE AND NO PRODUCT WAS LOST. THE VAPOR FILL HOSE WHILE ATTACHED TO A SAFETY BREAK AWAY BROKE THE NIPPLE IT IS COUPLED TO BEFORE THE SAFETY BREAKAWAY. THE EMPLOYEE IMMEDIATELY RESPONDED BY SHUTTING OFF THE MAIN SUPPLY VALVE WHICH WAS LOCATED 20 FEET AWAY. THE QUICK ACTIONS OF THE EMPLOYEE PREVENTED VERY LITTLE VAPOR TO ESCAPE. MEANWHILE, IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE INCIDENT, NEW SAFETY BREAKAWAY VALVES WERE INSTALLED, EVEN THOUGH THE ORIGINAL SAFETY BREAKAWAY VALVES WERE WITHIN THE GUIDELINES FOR STILL BEING IN SERVICE.

column168: THE PACKAGE WAS STOPPED AT DESTINATION BECAUSE OF ODOR AND IT APPEARED TO BE LEAKING. UPON OPENING THE PACKAGE IT WAS NOTICED THAT THERE WERE PLASTIC BAGS, EACH CONTAINING APPROXIMATELY 12-1OZ BOTTLES. THERE WERE A TOTAL OF APPROXIMATELY 288 BOTTLES IN THE PACKAGE. column168: WHILE LOADING BAGS IN FLIGHT 2120 MIA-ATL, EMPLOYEES SENSED A STRONG ODOR COMING OUT OF CANVAS BAG BELONGING TO PASSENGER MARTHA RIVAS. BAG WAS SET ASIDE AND LATER INSPECTED BY SECURITY AND ENVIRONMENTAL OFFICER WHO FOUND A .50 OZ GLASS BOTTLE OF NAIL STRENGTHENER BROKEN IN THE OUTSIDE LARGE POCKET OF THE BAG. THE .50 OZ SPILL WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE BAG LINING AND WAS DRY WHEN DISCOVERED. NO LIQUID WAS SPILLED OUTSIDE THE BAG LININGS. NO RESIDUES OF THE LIQUID, WET OR DIRED WERE VISIBLE IN THE OUTSIDE OF THE BAG. THE SMALL BOTTLE WAS PACKED WITHOUT PROTECTION, ABSORBENT,OR ANY KIND OF PACKAGING MATERIAL. THE HANDLING OF THE BAG, DROPPED OR THROWN IN CARTS AND AIRLINE EQUIPMENT MUST HAVE CONTRIBUTED TO THE SMALL GLASS BOTTLE FAILURE. BAG ORIGINATED IN MANAGUA, NICARAGUA, NO LEAK, SPILL OR STRONG ODOR REPORTED UPON ARRIVAL OR AT THE INS HALL AT MIA. BAG NOT LOADED IN FLIGHT 2120 MIS-ATL. PASSENGER INFORMED OF FUTURE PROPER PACKAGING OF THESE TYPE OF PRODUCTS.

column168: CHEMICAL SPILL INVOLVED TWO TOTES OF CORROSIVE LIQUID. ONE TOTE WAS PUNCTURED & BEGAN LEAKING WHEN UNLOADED FROM TRAILER. CHEMTREC WAS CALLED IMMEDIATELY. CHEMTREC HAD CONFERENCE CALL WITH SHIPPER & DISPATCHER. SPOKE WITH CHARLIE WEAVER AT SOLUTIONS PLUS AND EXPLAINED SITUATION. MR WEAVER ADVISED USING PRODUCT #SP1102, AN ALKALINE-BASED CLEANER THAT IS NOT HAZARDOUS TO PEOPLE. DOCK CONTRACTOR TILTED TOTE TO PREVENT PRODUCT FROM DRAINING OUT COMPLETELY. MR WEAVER SUPPLIED INFORMATION ON HOW TO TRANSFER PRODUCT INTO UNDAMAGED CONTAINER. TOLD MR WEAVER WE WOULD TELEPHONE CONSIGNEE & SEE IF THEY HAVE EMPTY TOTE WE COULD PICK UP ON THURSDAY, APRIL 4. TELEPHONED P.H. GLATFELTER, SPOKE TO DONNY WEAVER & EXPLAINED SITUATION. HE CHECK ON STATUS OF EMPTY TOTE & SAID WE COULD PICK UP AN EMPTY TOTE AT THEIR FACILITY TOMORROW, APRIL 4. MADE ARRANGEMENTS TO DO SO. TELEPHONED CHARLIE WEAVER (SHIPPER) & INFORMED HIM OF PLANS FOR SAVING/ TRANSFERRING REMAINING CLEANING SOLUTION. SPILL WAS ABSORBED WITH OIL DRY AND IS AWAITING PROPER DISPOSAL.
THE DRIVER OVERFILLED A 275 GALLON OIL TANK DUE TO THE VENT ALARM BEING INSTALLED IMPROPERLY. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED & CLEANED UP. CIFCO WILL INSTALL NEW VENT ALARM.

PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS BETH PARKER AND DONNIE OSBORNE DONNED THEIR PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND ENTERED THE LOWER BELLY COMPARTMENTS 1 AND 2 USING A PHOTO IONIZING DETECTOR TO DETERMINE WHICH PACKAGE OR PARCEL WAS EMITTING THE ODOR.   AFTER GOING THROUGH THEY FOUND A MANILLA PAPER TYPE PARCEL ENVELOPE THAT APPEARED TO HAVE A STAIN ON THE OUTSIDE AND THE DETECTOR INDICATED THAT THIS WAS THE SOURCE OF THE ODOR.  PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIAN BETH PARKER OPENED THE ENVELOPE AND DISCOVERED ANOTHER LIKE ENVELOPE INSIDE AND OPENED IT DISCOVERING 2 WHITE PLASTIC CONTAINERS. FURTHER INSPECTION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THERE WAS IN ONE OF THE PLASTIC CONTAINERS AN OIL SAMPLE WITH APPROXIMATELY 4 OUNCES (120 MLS) WHICH DID NOT LEAK.  TECHNICIAN PARKER THEN OPEN THE SECOND PLASTIC CONTAINER AND FOUND THE SOURCE OF THE ODOR AND THAT IT HAD LEAKED.  ALSO FOUND INSIDE WAS A CTC ANALYTICAL OIL SERVICES SAMPLE INFORMATION FORM THAT INDICATED THAT THE GASOLINE SAMPLE WAS TO BE TESTED FOR "SUGAR" FROM A GASOLINE TANK OF A 92 PLYMOUTH VOYAGER.  THE PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS PLACED THE PARCEL IN 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH AN ABSORBENT PAD AND RETURNED TO THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SORT FACILITY.  THE PARCEL IN QUESTION WAS THEN PLACED INTO A UN SPECIFICATION SALVAGE DRUM AND THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION IN THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SORT SECURITY CAGE. THERE WERE THREE EMPLOYEES WHO WAS IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR, BUT DID NOT REQUIRE MEDICAL TREATMENT OR FOLLOW UP, THEY IMMEDIATELY RESUMED UNLOADING THE AIRCRAFT INVOLVED.  THIS WAS A HIDDEN DISCREPANCY, THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS, OR A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS WAS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 0252 A.M.

column42: ORGANOCHLORINE PESTICIDES, LIQUID, TOXIC, FLAMMABLE, FLASH POINT NOT LESS THAN 23 DEGREES C
column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE LOADING, ONE WET CARTON CONTAINING TWO, TWO GALLON PLASTIC BOTTLES WAS DISCOVERED IN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. FURTHER INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT ONE BOTTLE WAS DAMAGED AND THE REMAINING ONE WAS UNAFFECTED. APPROXIMATELY, ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY ADJACENT FREIGHT. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENT PADS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A TWENTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE WET CARTON AND DAMAGED TWO GALLON PLASTIC BOTTLE WERE PLACED INTO A FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. BOTH RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE UNAFFECTED BOTTLE WAS REPACKAGED AND FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. ONE EMPLOYEE, KUKUMI FELETOA, HAD FREE PRODUCT ON HIS HANDS. MR. FELETOA WASHED HIS HANDS WITH SOAP AND WATER. MR. FELETOA WAS TAKEN TO THE PIONEER HOSPITAL IN WEST VALLEY CITY, UTAH AS A PRECAUTION. MR. FELETOA WAS SCENE AND RELEASED BACK TO WORK. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED. ALL FEDERAL, STATE AND LOCAL REGULATORY AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.

column42: AEROSOLS, FLAMMABLE, (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING WHILE IN THE FEDEX WAREHOUSE. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS DURING NORMAL SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES THERE WERE SEVERAL ITEMS IN THE SHIPMENT WHICH ARE BELIEVED TO BE DANGEROUS GOODS. THERE WERE ALSO SOME ITEMS NOT SUSPECTED TO BE DANGEROUS GOODS. AMONG THE ITEMS BELIEVED TO BE DANGEROUS GOODS INCLUDE: A) WD 40 PRODUCT, SAYS "FLAMMABLE", BELIEVED TO BE AEROSOL FLAMMABLE, 2.1 UN 1950, B) DOW DISINFECTANT BATHROOM CLEANER, AEROSOL, BELIEVED TO BE AEROSOL NONFLAMMABLE, 2.2, UN 1950, C) HYDROGEN PEROXIDE, POSSIBLY FLAMMABLE LIQUID N.O.S., 3 UN 1993, D) BESTINE SOLVENT & THINNER, BELIEVED TO BE FLAMMABLE LIQUID N.O.S., 3, UN1993, E) ISOPROPRYL ALCOHOL, BELIEVED TO BE FLAMMABLE LIQUID N.O.S., 3, UN 1993, F) CITRE SHINE HAIR SPRAY, SAYS "EXTREMELY FLAMMABLE" ON IT, BELIEVED TO BE FLAMMABLE LIQUID N.O.S., 3 UN 1993, AND G) DIAL ANTIBACTERIAL SOAP, POSSIBLY FLAMMABLE LIQUID N.O.S., 3 UN 1993. AS THE PACKAGE WAS NOT OFFERED BY THE SHIPPER WITH DANGEROUS GOODS MARKING, LABELING, OR A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS, IT IS BELIEVED TO BE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS. FAA AGENT KATHLEEN ROSCHER WAS NOTIFIED. THE PACKAGE WAS HELD AT FEDEX PENDING HER INVESTIGATION.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1105 HOURS(PDT)12 APRIL 2002 I WAS CONTACTED ADVISED THAT THERE WAS A FIRE AND HAZARDOUS MATERIAL (OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID) RELEASE AT THE APRIA HEALTHCARE BRANCH, 2150 N. TRABAJO DRIVE, OXNARD, CA 93030. I SPOKE VERY BRIEFLY, VIA TELEPHONE, WITH STEVE REINHART, LOGISTICS SUPERVISOR, WHO WAS AT THE SCENE. HE ADVISED THAT A MG INDUSTRIES CARGO TANK HAD BEEN MAKING A DELIVERY OF LIQUID, REFRIGERATED LIQUID TO THE BRANCH. AT APPROXIMATELY 1045 PDT THE DRIVER CAME TO THE DOOR YELLING THAT HIS TRUCK WAS ON FIRE. EMPLOYEES RESPONDED TO THE SCENE OF THE FIRE WITH FIRE EXTINGUISHERS BUT WERE NOT ABLE TO PUT THE FIRE OUT. THE OXNARD FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD ARRIVED ON THE SCENE. THE APRIA BUILDING AND SURROUNDING BUSINESSES HAD BEEN EVACUATED. THEY HAD ALSO SHUT DOWN THE 101 FREEWAY IN BOTH DIRECTIONS. IT WAS REPORTED THAT THERE WAS A RELEASE OF OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID, AND THE MG INDUSTRIES TRUCK, THE APRIA BULK TANK AND THE ASPHALT IN THE PARKING LOT WAS ON FIRE. HE THEN ADVISED ME THAT HIS ASSISTANCE HAD BEEN REQUESTED BY THE OXNARD FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE CALL WAS TERMINATED.  NUMEROUS ATTEMPTS WERE MADE TO RE-ESTABLISH CONTRACT.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1123 HOURS A THIRD PARTY ADVISED ME THAT SHE HAD BEEN ADVISED THAT THE MG INDUSTRIES TRUCK, APRIA BULK TANK AND THE ASPHALT AT THE BULK TANK WERE ON FIRE.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1135 HOURS CONTACT WAS RE-ESTABLISHED WITH STEVE REINHART WHO REPORTED THAT THE APRIA BULK TANK HAD NOT BEEN ON FIRE.  THE FIRE HAD BEEN LIMITED TO THE MG INDUSTRIES TRUCK. THE TRUCK HAD BEEN REMOVED FROM THE APRIA PROPERTY AND WAS NOW SITTING IN THE INTERSECTION OF TRABAJO DRIVE AND CAMINO AVENUE. THE TRUCK WAS STILL ON FIRE AND, BY ORDER OF THE OXNARD FIRE DEPARTMENT, THE OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID, WAS BEING VENTED TO RELEASE THE INTERNAL PRESSURE. OXNARD FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD DECLARED IT A MAJOR HAZMAT INCIDENT. THE EVACUATION WAS BEING CONTINUED AND THE 101 FREEWAY WAS STILL CLOSED TO ALL TRAFFIC IN BOTH DIRECTIONS AND HAD BEEN FOR OVER 30 TO 45 MINUTES. AT APPROXIMATELY 1138 HOURS I MADE CONTACT WITH MS. JONES AT THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND INITIATED CASE#02-20009.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1:00 PST THE EMPLOYEES WERE RELEASED TO RETURN TO THE BUILDINGS BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT IT WAS LATER ASCERTAINED THAT THE FIRE AND DAMAGE WAS LIMITED TOT HE REAR OF THE MG INDUSTRIES CARGO TANK TRAILER. THEIR INVESTIGATION IS CONTINUING. AT THIS TIME IT IS UNKNOWN IF THERE WAS A RELEASE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS OTHER THAN WHAT WHICH WAS VENTED AT THE DIRECTION OF FIRE PERSONNEL.

column168: GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES RECEIVED THE FIRST CALL ABOUT LIQUID LEAKING FROM A CONTAINER AT ABOUT 8:00. GARNER PERSONNEL LOADED UP EQUIPMENT AND ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AT 8:45. THEY THEN SUITED UP IN BUNKER GEAR AND OPEN CONTAINER. DRUMS WERE STACKED DOUBLED, FOUR WIDE THROUGHOUT THE CONTAINER. THERE WERE NO PALLETS SEPARATING THE UPPER AND LOWER DRUMS, JUST A PIECE OF PLYWOOD. AT 9:05 GARNER CALLED FOR AN EXTENDED BOOM FORKLIFT TO ASSIST IN REMOVING DRUMS TO LOCATE THE LEAKING DRUM. AT 9:28 GARNER CALLED EXTRA HELP TO ASSIST IN THE REMOVAL OF THE DRUMS FROM THE CONTAINER THEN RESTOCKING THEM SECURELY. AT 9:40 THE FORKLIFT AND OPERATOR AND EXTRA PERSONNEL ARE IN ROUTE. 10:00 SHERIFF DEPARTMENT ARRIVED ON SIGHT WITH QUESTION ABOUT THE LEAK. 10:08 THE REST STOP AREA AND RAMP ARE CLOSED TO THRU TRAFFIC. AT 10:38 FORKLIFT WITH OPERATOR ARRIVED AWAITING FIRE DEPARTMENT FOR STANDBY. 11:15 CLAY KENNELY WITH DPS HAZMAT RESPONSE ARRIVED. CURT CHATELAIN AND MYSELF (BRIAN HUDGINS) SUIT UP IN LEVEL B PPE TO START TAKING DRUMS FROM CONTAINER. LEVEL B WAS NECESSARY DUE TO THE CHEMICAL HAZARD. AT 11:55 SIX DRUMS WERE REMOVED FROM CONTAINER, CAUSE OF LEAK STILL NOT LOCATED. 12:15 RELIEF CREW SUITED UP IN LEVEL B AND CONTINUED TO REMOVE DRUMS FROM CONTAINER. 12:58  SECOND CREW FOUND LEAKING DRUM AND DISCUSSED WITH DPS ABOUT THE SAFEST WAY OF REMOVING AND SECURING LEAKING DRUM. 1:28 REMOVED LEAKING DRUM AND PLACED IN OVERPACK. RESUMED REMOVING SEVERAL OTHER CONTAMINATED DRUMS. 2:00 ALL CONTAMINATED DRUMS HAVE BEEN REMOVED AND DECONTAMINATED. 2:10  STARTED CLEANING THE FLOOR OF THE CONTAINER WITH MICROBLAZE TO REMOVE HAZARDOUS VAPORS. 3:38 LOADED ORIGINAL TRUCK BACK WITH DECONTAMINATED DRUMS WITH THREE LOAD LOCKS FOR STABILITY. 4:06 REMAINING DRUMS AND OVERPACK DRUM ARE LOADED ON TO SECOND TRUCK. 4:15 W.W. ROLLAND TRUCKS ARE RELEASED AND ALL GARNER EQUIPMENT, ALONG WITH STATE AND LOCAL OFFICIALS LEAVE THE SCENE.

E.M.I. JOB NUMBER: 15919 MS. WENDY FELLERS, CF TERMINAL IN ELLENWOOD, GEORGIA, CALLED EMI'S PETER HERNANDEZ AT 0913 ON APRIL 24, 2002 REGARDING A MINOR SPILL OF A CORROSIVE LIQUID CONTAINING SULFURIC ACID.  THE COMPOUND WAS INSIDE A 1 GALLON POLY PAIL AND WAS ONE OF NINE PAILS IN THREE CARDBOARD BOXES.  CF EMPLOYEES HAD FOUND THE CRUSHED BOX AND PAIL ON THE DOCK AFTER A TRAILER WAS UNLOADED.  IT WAS UNKNOWN WHICH TRAILER THE BOXES CAME FROM.  EMI CONTACTED HEPACO, INC. FROM TUCKER, GEORGIA TO RESPOND TO THE SPILLED ACID.  MEANWHILE, MR. HERNANDEZ CONTACTED ANDY GAY/CF DISTRICT SAFETY MANAGER WHO SAID IF IT WAS A MINOR SPILL, THAT CF EMPLOYEES COULD CLEAN IT THEMSELVES.  MR. HERNANDEZ THEN CANCELED HEPACO WHO DID NOT HAVE TO RESPOND.  APPARENTLY, CF EMPLOYEES CLEANED THE MINOR SPILL AND DISPOSED OF ANY WASTE GENERATED.  NO FURTHER ACTION WAS REQUIRED FROM EMI OR ITS SUBCONTRACTOR.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: E.M.I. JOB NUMBER: 15920-CF PERSONNEL DISCOVERED PALLET WITH 1-GALLON CONTAINERS HAD BEEN CRUSHED BY OTHER FREIGHT STACKED ON TOP.  CONTAINERS WERE CRUSHED AND NOT IN SHIPPABLE CONDITION.  APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS OF THE HYDROCHLORIC ACID SOLUTION WAS RELEASED.  CF PERSONNEL USED SODA ASH TO NEUTRALIZE AND CLEAN UP MATERIAL.  ALL CLEANUP MATERIAL AND DAMAGED CONTAINERS WERE PLACED IN A LINED OVERPACK DRUM.  THE OVERPACK DRUM WAS THEN LABELED AND SECURED PENDING DISPOSAL.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES IN REGARDS TO THIS INCIDENT.  E.M.I. NOTIFIED THE CF REGIONAL SAFETY MANAGER (MIKE KELLOUGH0) OF THE INCIDENT.

E.M.I. JOB NUMBER: 15923: CF PERSONNEL WERE UNLOADING FREIGHT FROM TRAILER #3-0011 AND DISCOVERED A CARTON WAS LEAKING.  THE CARTON WAS OPENED AND FOUND THAT A 1-GALLON CONTAINER OF ACETONITRILE WAS LEAKING DUE TO BEING CRUSHED.  APPROXIMATELY 1/2 PINT OF THE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  CF PERSONNEL USED ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO CLEAN UP RELEASE ON TRAILER FLOOR.  ALL CLEANUP MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN AN OVERPACK DRUM.  THE DRUM WAS LABELED AND MOVED TO A SECURE AREA PENDING DISPOSAL ARRANGEMENTS.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES IN REGARDS TO THIS RELEASE.

WAYNE ENGELKER WAS PULLING A PAIR OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA TRAILER ON HWY 138 WEST BOUND TO JULESBURG, CO.  THE REAR TANK BEGAN TO WHIP BACK AND FORTH THEN CAME LOOSE AND ROLLED INTO THE SOUTH DITCH OF THE HIGHWAY.  THE ROLL CAGE SHEARED OFF AND THE 3/4 INCHES PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE ALSO SHEARED OFF. AT THIS TIME A RELEASE BEGAN.  THE FRONT TRAILER ALSO ROLLED ONTO ITS SIDE AND LANDED IN THE SOUTH DITCH BUT NO RELEASE OCCURRED FROM THIS TANK.  THE REAR TANK RELEASED ITS CONTENTS WITH A GREATER PORTION OF THE PRODUCT VAPORIZING OFF TO THE ATMOSPHERE, WITH JUST A LITTLE POOLING OF PRODUCT IN THE DITCH AREA.  EXAMINATION OF THE REAR HITCH OF THE FRONT TRAILER SHOWED A TWISTING OF THE HITCH PRIOR TO THE HITCH BEING TORE OFF THE TRAILER. FURTHER EXAMINATION INDICATED A FRESH BREAK OF THE WELD AS THERE WAS NO RUST PRESENT IN THE WELD AREA WERE IT WAS PULLED APART FROM THE TRAILERS RUNNING GEAR.  IN SUMMARY I BELIEVE THIS ACCIDENT WAS THE RESULT OF EXCESSIVE SPEED ON THE PART OF THE DRIVER OR NEGLIGENCE ON HIS PART.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: THE DRIVER HAD LOADED A LOAD OF DIESEL FUEL IN DULCE N.M. WAS TRAVELING TO BLOOMFIELD N.M. THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF THE TRUCK. THE TRUCK OVERTURNED ONTO ITS LIFT SIDE & THE GUARD RAIL PUNCTURED THE CARGO TANK & SPILLED OUT 7500 GAL OF DIESEL FUEL. OFFICES KEVIN GARLINGTON WAS THE N.M. HAZ MAT OFFICE CALLED TO THE SCENE.  MR. JOHNNY DUFUR THE TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MGR FOR SIEVA WEST WAS NOTIFIED AT 0045 HE CALLED ENVIROTIC CLEAN UP THEY ARRIVED WITHIN 20 MINUTES WITH A CLEAN UP CREW & BEGAN STABILIZATION & CLEAN -UP OF THE 7500 GALLONS OF SPILLED DIESEL FUEL. AT ABOUT 0050 KEVIN GARLINGTON OF THE NM STATE POLICE ADVISED HIS DISPATCH TO CONTACT E.P.A. TO REPORT THIS INCIDENT IN ORDER FOR A FOLLOWUP SUPERVISOR OF THE CLEAN UP. THE CLEAN UP IS STILL UNDER-WAY. I HAVE NO DOLLAR FIGURES ON THE COST OF THE CLEAN UP OR THE COST OF THE GUARD-RAIL.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column42: AEROSOLS, FLAMMABLE, (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column168: WHILE LOADING BAGS IN FLIGHT 1709 MIA SJU, FLEET SERVICE CLERKS SENSED A STRONG ODOR EMANATING FROM A CANVAS ROLLABOARD TYPE BAG BELONGING TO PASSENGER KEVIN DONOVAN. THE ENVIRONMENTAL COORDINATOR J. RAMIREZ RESPONDED AND AFTER INVESTIGATION FOUND THAT THE BAG CONTAINED AN AEROSOL CAN OF SPRAY STARCH THAT HAD EXPELLED ALL THE 22 OZ OF STARCH. THE CAN HAD A GASH OF APPROXIMATELY ONE HALF OF AN INCH HOWEVER HAD NO VISIBLE PUNCTURES. THE AEROSOL CAN HAD THE CAP WHEN FOUND. NO OBJECTS INSIDE THE BAGS WERE FOUND TO HAVE CAUSED THE DAMAGE TO THE CAN. BAG CONTAINED CLOTHES, TOILETRY ITEMS, HOUSEHOLD PRODUCTS AND GROCERY PRODUCTS AND CANS. THE EXPELLED STARCH WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE BAG AND WAS MOSTLY ABSORBED BY THE ARTICLES INSIDE IT. THE BAG WAS NOT LOADED IN FLIGHT 1709, WAS CLEANED UP, ALLOWED TO DRY AND THEN SENT ON FIRST AVAILABLE FLIGHT TO SJU. PASSENGER WAS INFORMED OF FUTURE PROPER PACKAGING AND TRANSPORTATION OF DANGEROUS GOODS.
column172: Cloth or burlap bag (cont1 for solid materials)

column168: DONNIE, RAMP SUPERVISOR, REPORTED HE OBSERVED AN INTERMODAL TANK LEAKING AND REQUESTED HAZMAT PERSONNEL BE NOTIFIED TO RESPOND.  DONNIE REPORTED INTERMODAL TANK AWXU 630117 WAS LOCATED AT RAMP NUMBER TWO OF THE SEATTLE YARD AND ADVISED THERE WAS A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL ON THE TOP OF THE TANK, ALONG THE SIDE OF THE TANK, AND ON THE RAILCAR ITSELF.  VERN LIBBY, SPECIAL AGENT - HAZMAT, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  SPECIAL AGENT LIBBY, REPORTED THAT THE MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE SPILLBOX, THE RIGHT REAR OF THE RAILCAR, AND THE SIDE OF THE INTERMODAL TANK.  JOHN, CHEMTREC, WAS NOTIFIED AND PROVIDED REPORT NUMBER 04032002021.  LIBBY DISCOVERED TWO LOOSE MANWAY BOLTS, WHICH HE SECURED TO STOP THE LEAK.  CHAMPION TECHNOLOGIES CONTRACTED FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL, AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, TO CLEAN THE INTERMODAL TANK AND THE RAILCAR.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column168: MARK REIMERS, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER, REPORTED THE COUNCIL BLUFFS CAR DEPARTMENT INFORMED HIM THAT TANKCAR NATX 37862 LEAKED DENATURED ALCOHOL FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE IN THE COUNCIL BLUFF UP YARD AT FOX PARK.  INSPECTION OF THE CAR BY MGR. REIMERS REVEALED THE CAR LEAKING AT A RATE OF ONE DROP EVERY 10 SECONDS.  MGR. REIMERS REPORTED THAT THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS SLIGHTLY OPEN AND HE HAD CLOSED THE VALVE COMPLETELY.  HE ALSO REPORTED THAT THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP GASKET WAS DETERIORATED AND HE FASHIONED A GASKET OUT OF GORE-TEX AND REPLACED THE CAP.  THESE ACTIONS STOPPED THE LEAK.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.

column168: BILL WILKIE, YARDMASTER, REPORTED LARRY PENA, CAR FOREMAN, ADVISED AN ODOR WAS NOTICED AT THE ONE SPOT AREA IN THE COLTON YARD.  DUFFY EXON, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  MANAGER EXON REPORTED HE AND ROBERT BAVIER, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION, WERE ON THE SCENE AND AN ODOR WAS NOTICED FROM TANKCAR ASTX 5005.  AFTER THEIR INSPECTION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE LIQUID EDUCATION LINE CAP AND ONE MANWAY COVER BOLT WERE LOOSE.  BOTH WERE TIGHTENED AND THE VAPOR RELEASE WAS STOPPED.  MR. BAVIER REQUESTED STATE, COUNTY, AND CHEMTREC NOTIFICATIONS BE MADE BY THE RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION CENTER.

column168: WHILE CONDUCTING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS AT GREEN RIVER WYO. FRA INSPECTOR BRUCE MARRIOTT OBSERVED TANKCAR GATX 40014 TO BE OUT OF COMPLIANCE, AS FOLLOWS, LIQUID VALVE LEFT PARTIALLY OPEN, PLUG NOT APPLIED, AND PROTECTIVE HOUSING OPEN.  CAR WAS WET WITH PRODUCT.  CAR DEPT. EMPLOYEES MADE THE REPAIRS BY PROPERLY APPLYING THE PLUG AND CLOSING THE VALVE AND SECURING THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING.  CAR CONTINUED TO DESTINATION. SHIPPER ONYX ENVIRONMENTAL INFORMED (303-289-4827) AND CHEMTREC NOTIFIED.

ON SUNDAY, 4/7/02, TANK CAR GATX 5640 WAS BEING MOVED DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS AT THE UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD YARD AT LIVONIA, LA.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR AND SEVERAL DROPS CONTACTED SWITCHMAN HARRY MURRAY ON THE CHEEK AND ARM.  MR. MURRAY WASHED THE ACID OFF WITH COPIOUS AMOUNTS OF WATER AND AN ACID NEUTRALIZER FROM A FIRST AID KIT.  MR. MURRAY DECLINED FURTHER MEDICAL TREATMENT.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED TO THE HAZ/MAT TRACK AT THE LIVONIA YARD WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT AND NO FURTHER PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  UPON NOTIFICATION UPRR MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, T. M. ROBINSON RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  WHILE EN ROUTE ROBINSON WAS ADVISED THAT THE SHIPPER HAD DISPATCHED HULCHER SERVICES TO SECURE AND DECONTAMINATE THE CAR.  ROBINSON WAS CONTACTED AT THE SCENE BY MR. KEITH LEBLANC OF HULCHER SERVICES.  HULCHER TECHNICIANS UNDER MR. LEBLANC'S SUPERVISION INSPECTED THE CAR AND DETERMINED THAT THE LEAKAGE HAD COME FROM THE QUICK FILL PORT.  THE THREE SWING BOLTS THAT SECURE THE QUICK FILL PORT COVER WERE LOOSE.  HULCHERS INSPECTION INDICATED THAT THERE WAS ADEQUATE OUTAGE.  THE LOOSE BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED AND THIS SECURED THE CAR.  WATER WAS USED TO DECONTAMINATE THE SMALL AMOUNT OF SPILLAGE ON THE CAR.  IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT ADDITIONAL NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE, THE LOUISIANA DEPT. OF ENV. QUALITY AND THE POINTE COUPEE SHERIFF'S OFFICE.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: CTS MGR LERCH WAS ADVISED THAT ED HARRIS OF NORTHWEST PIPE, HOUSTON, TX., HAD REPORTED RECEIVING A GONDOLA CAR COVERED WITH A SOFT TARP.  INSPECTION OF THE CAR BY MR ED HARRIS AND MR BUDDY BREWER REVEALED THAT THE CAR WAS LOADED WITH DIRT AND WATER.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION DEVELOPED THAT THE CAR CONTAINED HAZARDOUS WASTE SOLID, NOS.  MR HARRIS AND MR BREWER BECAME CONCERNED BECAUSE THEY HAD COME IN CONTACT WITH THE WATER THAT WAS IN THE CAR.  AFTER LEARNING THAT THERE HAD BEEN AN EXPOSURE, THE SHIPPER, SAFETY KLEEN WAS NOTIFIED.  MR HARRIS INFORMED MGR LERCH THAT RAIN WATER WAS DROPPING FROM THE CAR DUE TO A RECENT RAIN STORM.  INVESTIGATION DEVELOPED THAT CAR CNW 340377, A LOAD OF CONTAMINATED SOIL HAD BEEN BILLED TO NORTHWEST PIPE IN ERROR.  MGR LERCH CONTACTED MR HARRIS TO ADVISE HIM THAT THE CAR WOULD BE RE-BILLED TO SAFETY KLEEN.  MR HARRIS THEN INFORMED MGR LERCH THAT THE CAR WAS CONTINUING TO LEAK.  FLOOR DRY HAD BEEN APPLIED AROUND THE CAR TO CONTAIN AND ABSORB THE LIQUID.  INSPECTION OF THE CAR BY MGR LERCH REVEALED THAT THE COVER HAD BEEN REMOVED BY MR HARRIS WHEN HE HAD INSPECTED THE CAR.  RAIN WATER HA DRAINED INTO THE CAR AND WAS ABSORBED BY THE CONTAMINATED SOIL.  AS THE SOIL BECAME SATURATED WITH THE RAIN WATER, IT DRAINED FROM THE INTERIOR OF THE CAR TO THE GROUND VIA VARIOUS CRACKS AND HOLES ON THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR.  THE WATER WAS NOW ALSO CONTAMINATED AND WOULD HAVE TO BE RECOVERED.  ADDITIONALLY, THE CONTAMINATED SOIL WOULD HAVE TO BE TRANSLOADED TO ANOTHER CAR DUE TO THE POOR INTEGRITY OF THE ORIGINAL CAR AND BECAUSE OF THE CAR BEING OVERWEIGHT DUE TO THE SOIL MOISTURE CONTENT FROM THE RAIN WATER.  MGR LERCH THEN INFORMED MR HARRIS DUE THE CIRCUMSTANCES CREATED BY THE RAIN WATER, SPECIAL HANDLING OF THE CAR WOULD BE REQUIRED.  THE CAR COULD NOT BE MOVED FROM HIS FACILITY UNTIL PROPER ARRANGEMENTS COULD BE MADE TO SECURE IT FROM ANY FURTHER LEAKAGE. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE FOR SAFETY KLEEN PERSONNEL TO RESPOND, CONTAIN THE CAR FROM ANY FURTHER LEAKAGE, AND TRANSLOAD THE CONTAMINATED SOIL INTO ROLL-OFF CONTAINERS.  THE CONTAINERS WOULD THEN BE TRUCKED TO SAFETY KLEENS DEER PARK FACILITY FOR DISPOSAL.
column172: Rail hopper car for solid materials only

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: DOYLE TEMPLETON, MANAGER OF TRAIN OPERATIONS-PARONS KS, REPORTED TANKCAR UCLX 30055 LEAKED FROM THE TOP WHEN IT WAS MOVED.  THE CREW TIED THE CAR DOWN IN PRYOR OK NORTH OF THE DEPOT ON THE ENGINE TRACK.  MR. TEMPLETON REPORTED HE MADE CONTACT WITH PROTEIN TECHNOLOGIES, CONSIGNEE, IN PRYOR. MIKE KELLY, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER, WAS NOTIFIED AND CONTRACTED WITH SOONER EMERGENCY SERVICES TO RESPOND TO THE RELEASE.  MGR. KELLY REQUESTED STATE NOTIFICATIONS BE MADE BY RMCC.  MGR KELLY REPORTED SOONER EMERGENCY SERVICES PERSONNEL DISCOVERED THE SWING BOLT ON THE QUICK FILL PORT LOOSE.  THE BOLT WAS TIGHTENED AND THE CAR WAS INSPECTED, SECURED AND RELEASED.  THE NEXT MORNING WHEN THE CAR WAS MOVED BY THE SWITCHING CREW VAPORS AGAINED APPEARED FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  KELLY CONTACTED VULCAN AND THE ADVISED THAT THEY WOULD INSPECT THE CAR.  VULCAN PERSONNEL ADVISED THAT THE FRANGIBLE DISK HAD ALSO FAILED ON THE CAR.  THEY REPLACED THE DISK AND THE CAR WAS ALLOWED TO CONTINUE ONTO IT'S DESTINATION.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Piping or Fittings
column168: JACK VAIL, FEDERAL RAILROAD ADMINISTRATION, REPORTED A FIFTY GALLON SULFURIC ACID SPILL ON THE GROUND AT J R SIMPLOT IN EL CENTRO, CA.  MR VAIL INQUIRED ABOUT THE INCIDENT AND RMCC HAD NO INFORMATION.  DENNIS JOHNSON, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER, WAS NOTIFIED AND WAS UNAWARE OF THE INCIDENT.  GARY HUTNER, MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND WAS ALSO UNAWARE OF THE INCIDENT.  MGR. HUTNER INVESTIGATED AND ADVISED THAT TANKCAR TCDX 13269, LEAKED SULFURIC ACID FROM A GASKET UNDER THE TANKCAR AT THE BOTTOM.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED ACCORDING TO THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ON SCENE. THE TANKCAR WAS ON J R SIMPLOT PROPERTY AND WAS DRIPPING PRODUCT AT THE RATE OF TEN TO FIFTEEN DROPS PER MINUTE.  THE TANK CAR WAS FOUR HUNDRED FEET FROM THE CALEXICO MAINLINE.  THERE WAS NO EVACUATION AND NO WATERWAYS WERE INVOLVED.  DENNIS JOHNSON, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER ADVISED THAT THE TANK CAR HAD BEEN SPOTTED AT THE CUSTOMER'S PLANT FOR TWO DAYS.  THE LEAK WAS OBSERVED DURING THE OFF LOADING PROCESS.  JACK VAIL, FEDERAL RAILROAD ADMINISTRATION WAS UPDATED.  EL CENTRO FIRE DEPT. REPORTED THAT OVER 1000 GALLONS OF STANDING PRODUCT WAS REMOVED FROM THE GROUND AND CLEAN UP WOULD INVOLVE REMOVAL OF THE SPUR TRACK AND SURROUNDING CONTAMINATED SOIL.

THE MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS IN GREEN RIVER, REPORTED TANKCAR GATX 27387, LOADED WITH SODIUM SILICATE, UN 1719, WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR. IT WAS REPORTED THAT TWELVE INCH STREAK OF PRODUCT WAS OBSERVED CRYSTALLIZED ON THE SIDE OF THE CAR.  MARK REIMERS, REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION AND SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND CONFERRED WITH FACILITY PERSONNEL.  MR. REIMERS DISPATCHED ROCKY MOUNTAIN CATASTROPHE, AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INSPECT AND REPAIR THE CAR.  MGR REIMERS REPORTED THAT THE RELEASE WAS CAUSED BY A MISAPPLIED MANWAY COVER GASKET. REPOSITIONING OF THE GASKET AND TIGHTENING OF THE COVER STOPPED THE LEAK AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.  NONE OF THE SPILLED PRODUCT REACHED THE GROUND.

ANNETTE, MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS, REPORTED TANKCAR DOWX 6999 WAS LOCATED ON TRACK SIX IN THE VELASCO YARD IN FREEPORT, TX AND WAS VENTING FROM THE TOP.  ANNETTE STATED THE TANKCAR WAS LOADED WITH HYDROCHLORIC ACID AND DENNIS WOOSTER, DOW CHEMICAL, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDING.  REGIONAL MGR. CTS, TIM O'BRIEN REPORTED DENNIS WOOSTER HAD REPORTED THAT THE TANKCAR WAS VENTING FROM A VALVE ON THE TOP OF THE CAR.  MR WOOSTER CLEANED OFF THE VALVE AND CHECKED FOR LEAKS.  MR. WOOSTER LATER ADVISED MGR O'BRIEN THAT HE DID NOT FIND ANY PRODUCT LEAKS AND SUSPECTED A WEAK SPRING IN THE VALVE. MR O'BRIEN STATED THE TANKCAR WOULD BE SHOVED BACK INTO THE PLANT IN THE MORNING FOR A CLOSER INSPECTION.

LANE A. SEKAVEC, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS NOTIFIED BY DARRELL HORNICK, DIRECTOR OF TERMINAL OPERATIONS, OF A LEAK FROM TANKCAR FLIX 2552, A LOAD OF PHOSPHORIC ACID.  MR. SEKAVEC MADE CONTACT WITH JACK CURRY, FARMLAND INDUSTRIES, TO VERIFY CHEMICAL PROPERTIES.  UPON ARRIVAL AT NEFF YARD, MR. SEKAVEC COMPLETED AN INSPECTION OF THE CAR AND FOUND THE BARREL GASKET WAS OUT OF PLACE.  MR. SEKAVEC REPOSITIONED THE GASKET AND RESECURED THE CAR.  THE OUTSIDE OF THE CAR WAS DECONTAMINATED WITH A DILUTED SOLUTION OF BAKING SODA AND THEN RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION TO DESTINATION.

ROBERT BAVIER, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, REPORTED VAPOR WAS RELEASED FROM THE MANWAY COVER ON TANKCAR JRSX 1101 LOCATED ON TRACK 314 IN THE COLTON YARD.  MR BAVIER STATED WITH THE ASSISTANCE OF BEN SOWARDS, SPECIAL AGENT, THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED AND THE RELEASE WAS STOPPED. MR. BAVIER ADVISED NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO STATE AND COUNTY AGENCIES, THE SAN BERNARDINO COUNTY DISTRICT ATTORNEY'S OFFICE, AND CHEMTREC.

JAMES LACKEY, MANAGER YARD OPERATIONS, REPORTED A CONDUCTOR REPORTED TANKCAR UTLX 202902 LEAKED METHANOL PRODUCT FROM THE TOP OF THE TANKCAR. MR. LACKEY REPORTED THE RAILCAR WAS LOCATED AT RAIL 205, FORTY RAILCARS FROM THE NORTH END.  KENNETH SIMPSON, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  TAM, CHEMTREC, WAS NOTIFIED.  MGR SIMPSON REPORTED HE TIGHTENED A THREE INCH FILLER VALVE ON THE TOP OF THE RAILCAR ONTO THE THREE INCH NIPPLE WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.

BUTCH RHODES CONTACTED RMCC ABOUT A LEAKING TANK CAR UTLX 202969 AT N LITTLE ROCK, AR YARDS.  KENNETH SIMPSON, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  MR SIMPSON SECURED THE LIQUID VALVE, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.

THE COUNCIL BLUFFS YARDMASTER, REPORTED TANKCAR ACFX 87839 APPEARED TO BE DRIPPING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR WITH THE SIDE OF THE CAR BEING WET.  THE CAR CAME INTO COUNCIL BLUFFS ON TRAIN MKCCB 18.  MARK REIMERS, REGIONAL MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED.  MR. REIMERS REPORTED THE MANWAY GASKET WAS SEVERELY DEGRADED, RESULTING IN THE RELEASE. MR. REIMERS REPLACED THE GASKET WITH GORTEX ROPE, AND TIGHTENED DOWN THE MANWAY COVER.  NONE OF THE SPILLED PRODUCT REACHED THE GROUND.  MR. REIMERS THEN NOTED THAT THE PLACARDING FOR THE CAR DID NOT MATCH THE BILLING INFORMATION.  AFTER AN INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE PLACARDING WAS CORRECT, AND THE BILLING FOR THE CAR WAS WRONG.  THE NCSC AMENDED THE BILLING AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.

RONNIE WOMACK, CAR FOREMAN, REPORTED A FOUL ODOR SIMILAR TO ROTTEN EGGS, WAS EMITTED FROM AN UNKNOWN TANKCAR LOCATED ON TRACK NUMBER 205 AT THE NORTH LITTLE ROCK INBOUND YARD.  JOHN STEWART, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  BILL DONNER, SPECIAL AGENT, REPORTED THE TERMINAL HAD EVACUATED THE YARD FOR PRECAUTIONARY PURPOSES. RMCC TO NOTIFIED TIM O'BRIEN, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY REGIONAL MANAGER, WHO REQUESTED THAT RMCC NOTIFY THE CENTER FOR TOXICOLOGY AND ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH.  MGR. STEWART REPORTED HE WAS ON THE SCENE AND TANKCAR CELX 23602 WAS BELIEVED TO BE THE ORIGIN OF THE RELEASE.  MR. STEWART STATED THE ODOR WAS NOT STRONG AND REQUESTED RMCC TO NOTIFY CHEMTREC.  MGR. STEWART REPORTED LOOSE NUTS LOCATED ON THE FLANGE FOR THE LIQUID VALVE WERE TIGHTENED AND THE RELEASE WAS STOPPED.  MR. STEWART STATED AIR READINGS CONDUCTED BY MR. MILNER, CENTER FOR TOXICOLOGY AND ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH, WERE OF GOOD QUALITY AND THE EVACUATION WAS LIFTED. MR. STEWART INSTRUCTED RMCC TO PROVIDE COURTESY NOTIFICATION TO THE APPROPRIATE STATE AGENCIES AND THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT.  THE APPROPRIATE AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.  THE TANKCAR WAS SET OUT AT THE NORTH LITTLE ROCK YARD FOR AN INSPECTION BY A CELANESE CLEARLAKE REPRESENTATIVE.  ON 04/22/02 AT 03:05 AM, JAMIE LACKEY, MANAGER YARD OPERATIONS, ADVISED TANKCAR CELX 23602 WAS AGAIN LEAKING AND RELEASING AN ODOR IN THE YARD.  MR. LACKEY REPORTED THE RAILCAR WAS LOCATED AT THE EAST END OF TRACK 57 IN THE NORTH LITTLE ROCK YARD.  MGR STEWART WAS CONTACTED.  AT 6:00 AM, MGR. STEWART, KENNETH SIMPSON, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER, ALONG WITH DR. GLEN MELNER, CTEH, A CLEARLAKE REPRESENTATIVE, AND PERSONNEL FROM ER CONTRACTOR RESPONDED TO THE YARD.  MR. STEWART ADVISED THE TANKCAR WAS NOT LEAKING AND NO ODOR WAS RELEASED UNTIL THE TANKCAR WAS MOVED.  MR. STEWART REPORTED IT WAS STILL UNKNOWN WHERE THE ODOR WAS BEING RELEASED FROM AND ADDITIONAL TESTS WERE BEING CONDUCTED.  AT 07:10 AM, MGR. STEWART ADVISED THAT THE MANWAY GASKET WAS CHANGED OUT AND AFTER A THOROUGH INSPECTION, THE TANKCAR WOULD BE RELEASED.

TANKCAR TEIX 16121, RELEASED 5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT FROM TOP OF CAR DUE TO IMPROPERLY SECURED LIQUID EDUCATION LINE VALVE.  ALL PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED TO THE TOP AND SIDES OF CAR.  THE VALVE WAS SECURED AND SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  THE SHIPPER MOBILIZED THEIR CONTRACTOR TO NEUTRALIZE AND CLEAN THE TOP AND SIDES OF CAR.  AFTER THE CAR WAS CLEANED, IT WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.  ALL NECESSARY NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.

KENNY GOMEZ, MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS, ADVISED OF A STRONG ODOR EMANATING FROM A TANKCAR AND ADVISED TOM ROBINSON, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  THE TANKCAR WAS ISOLATED ON HAZMAT TRACK 105 IN THE LIVONIA YARD.  MR. GOMEZ REPORTED THERE WAS NO VISIBLE SIGN OF A LEAK BUT ADVISED THE ODOR WAS RATHER STRONG.  MGR. ROBINSON REPORTED HE ARRIVED ON SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 03:35 AM AND ADVISED HE COMPLETED THE INSPECTION OF THE TANKCAR IN QUESTION.  MR. ROBINSON REPORTED HE DISCOVERED A SLIGHT VAPOR RELEASE FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE AND ADVISED THIS WAS DUE TO A POSSIBLE DEFECTIVE O RING.  MR. ROBINSON WAS CONFERRED WITH DAVID OUBRE, TRIAD NITROGEN INCORPORATED - SHIPPER, WHO ADVISED HE WOULD CONTACT EAGLE CONSTRUCTION, ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR, TO RESPOND AND MAKE REPAIRS TO THE TANKCAR IN QUESTION.  MR. ROBINSON REPORTED HE WOULD REMAIN ON SCENE UNTIL THE REPAIRS WERE COMPLETED.  ROBINSON REPORTED THAT SHIPPERS REPRESENTATIVES MR. DAVID OUBRE AND MR. RICHARD BARTLEY ALONG WITH TWO TECHNICIANS FROM CONTRACTOR EAGLE CONST. & ENV. CO. ARRIVED ON SCENE AT ABOUT 0630 HOURS.  THE O-RINGS IN THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WERE REPLACED AND THE LEAK WAS SECURED.  THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE AND CHEMTREC WERE NOTIFIED.

CURTIS HUCKABY, MANAGER YARD OPERATIONS, REPORTED AN UNKNOWN AMOUNT OF PRODUCT SPILLED FROM THE MANWAY COVER ON TANKCAR GATX 19912 AND DOWN THE SIDES OF THE TANKCAR DURING HUMPING OPERATIONS ON BOWL TRACK 21 IN THE SETTEGAST YARD.  MR. HUCKABY FURTHER STATED NO PERSONNEL WERE INJURED AND NO PRODUCT WAS ON THE GROUND.  CRAIG DENNY, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  MGR. DENNY REPORTED LOOSE BOLTS ON THE LIQUID LINE WERE TIGHTENED AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: DENNIS JOHNSON, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, REPORTED WHILE PERFORMING A ROUTINE INSPECTION WITH THE FRA AND ARIZONA CORPORATION COMMISSION INSPECTORS ON TANKCARS RETURNING FROM MEXICO, TANKCAR CITX 35061 WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE A STRIPPED OUT PACKING GLAND NUT ON THE GAUGING DEVICE, LEAKING A SMALL AMOUNT OF VAPOR. THE CAR WAS SET OUT AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED. THE SHIPPER (DYNEGY) WAS CONTACTED. DYNEGY CONTACTED AND CONTRACTED WITH AN ER CONTRACTOR IN PHOENIX, AZ. TO RESPOND AND MAKE FIELD REPAIRS.  ON 5-1-2002, CONTRACTOR ERI ARRIVED AT TUCSON AND UPON INVESTIGATION IT WAS NOTED THAT THE THREADS ON THE PACKING GLAND NUT WERE STRIPPED CAUSING THE PACKING GLAND NOT TO TIGHTEN ALLOWING THE VAPOR LEAK. THE CONTRACTOR APPLIED A METAL EPOXY AROUND THE GAUGING ROD AND THE PACKING GLAND NUT TO STOP THE LEAK. THE SHIPPER DYNEGY IS RESPONSIBLE FOR OBTAINING MOVEMENT AUTHORITY FROM THE FRA DUE TO THIS FIELD REPAIRS. THIS CAR WAS MOVING AS A RESIDUE RETURNING TO RICHMOND, CALIF. AFTER BEING OFF LOADED IN MEXICO.

MIKE POLLARD, MANAGER OF TERMINAL OPERATIONS, REPORTED A POSSIBLE LEAKING TANKCAR AT THE CENTENNIAL YARD AND REQUESTED A HAZMAT AGENT BE NOTIFIED TO RESPOND AND INVESTIGATE. MR. POLLARD REPORTED CREWS WERE COMPLAINING OF A STRONG ODOR RESEMBLING ROTTEN EGGS AND ADVISED THE ODOR SEEMED TO BE EMANATING FROM THE DEPARTURE YARD.  ED MCNUTT, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. AT 02:48 AM, MGR ED MCNUTT REPORTED TANKCAR GATX 3887, LOADED WITH AMMONIUM SULFIDE, WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE RELEASED LESS THAN ONE POUND OF MATERIAL FROM THE MANWAY COVER AND ADVISED THE MANWAY COVER WAS INSPECTED AND SECURED. MR. MCNUTT REPORTED HE COMPLETED AN INSPECTION OF THE ENTIRE TANKCAR AND ADVISED NO FURTHER IRREGULARTIES WERE DETECTED. MR. MCNUTT REQUESTED CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER BE NOTIFIED BY RMCC.

E.M.I. JOB NUMBER: 16024. THE SHIPPER PUT THREE METAL CYLINDERS-STEEL FLASKS (EACH APPROXIMATELY 6" DIA X 12" HIGH) CONTAINING 160 POUNDS OF MERCURY INTO A SEALED WOODEN CRATE. THE SCREW-ON CAPS WERE NOT TIGHTENED BY THE SHIPPER (PER AN INTERVIEW WITH THE SHIPPER'S REPRESENTATIVE) AND THE SCREW TOPS LOOSENED ENROUTE WITH ONE ACTUALLY COMING COMPLETELY OFF OF THE CYCLINDER. THE RESULT WAS A RELEASE OF AN ESTIMATED 92 POUNDS OF MERCURY. THE INCIDENT WAS DISCOVERED AT THE CONSOLIDATED FREIGHTWAYS TERMINAL IN HOUSTON. A EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM INITIATED CLEAN UP ACTIVITIES  WHICH COLLECTED TEN POUNDS IN THE TRAILER AT THE HOUSTON TERMINAL. AN INTERVIEW WITH THE DRIVER IDENTIFIED TWO STOPPING POINTS BETWEEN DALLAS, TX AND HOUSTON. I RESPONDED TO A SPILL ON THE ORANGE BELT. I USED THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET FOR UNKNOWN. RESPONSE SHEET FOR UNKNOWN HAD ME PERFORM A LITMUS TEST. THE LITMUS TEST READ PH BALANCE NEUTRAL RANGE. RESPONSE SHEET AND RESULT OF LITMUS TEST, HAD ME USE RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUID. RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUID HAD ME USE CLAY ABSORBENT TO ABSORB ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL. ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS PLACE IN A LINED TRAY AND, AFTERWARDS; ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS TAKEN TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. PROPER PACKAGE HANDLING COULD HAVE PREVENTED THE SPILL. THE REMAINING SIX PLASTIC CONTAINERS WERE SENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER IN EXCELLENT CONDITION.

I RESPONDED TO A SPILL ON THE ORANGE BELT. I USE THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET FOR ORM-D. RESPONSE SHEET FOR ORM-D HAD ME PERFORM A LITMUS TEST. THE LITMUS TEST PH 13 BALANCE RANGE. column168: DRUM HAD A CRACK IN IT.  SCOTT FROM F.M.C. CAME UP & CLEANED & DISPOSED OF.

MID KANSAS COOP BUHLER NH3 FACILITY, 1/2 MILE WEST OF THE N VICTORY ROAD & E 69TH AVENUE INTERSECTION.  DELIVERY OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA WAS BEING MADE TO MID KANSAS COOP (MKC) STORAGE FACILITY AT APPROXIMATELY 9:30 AM.  HOSE CONNECTIONS WERE ALL MADE FROM TRANSPORT TO STORAGE AND AS DELIVERY DRIVER OPENED THE LIQUID VALVE A BLEEDER HOSE RELEASED A CLOUD OF VAPORIZED AMMONIA INTO THE AIR.  THIS CLOUD WAS IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA OF THE VALVES FOR BOTH TRANSPORT AND STORAGE MAKING IT UNSAFE TO CLOSE VALVES WITHOUT EMERGENCY ASSISTANCE.  AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT IT WAS UNCLEAR AS TO WHAT WAS CAUSING THE RELEASE AND WHAT (IF ANYTHING) HAD FAILED.  911 WERE CALLED AND THE LOCAL BUHLER FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED.  THEY RESPONDED WITH EMERGENCY EQUIPMENT AND PERSONNEL USING WATER FOG AND BREATHING EQUIPMENT TO CLOSE VALVES AND SHUT OFF RELEASE.  AFTER THE RELEASE WAS SHUT OFF IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THERE HAD BEEN NO EQUIPMENT FAILURE.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE VALVE ON THE HOSE USED TO BLEED THE TRANSPORT CONNECTION INTO A WATER TANK HAD BEEN LEFT OPEN.  THIS COULD HAVE BEEN CAUSED BY EITHER A) THE PREVIOUS DELIVERY AND NOT CLOSING THE VALVE OR B) SOME PERSON THAT WAS ATTEMPTING TO STEAL NH3 FOR THE PURPOSE OF MAKING METHAMPHETAMINE.  WE DETERMINED THAT IT WAS THE LAST THING, BECAUSE THE HOSE WAS SECURED INTO THE WATER TANK PRIOR TO THIS SO THIS VERY THING WOULD NOT HAPPEN WHEN THE CONNECTION PRESSURE WAS RELEASED.  TELEPHONE CALLS WERE MADE IN THE FOLLOWING ORDER: LOCAL 911 TIME: APPROX 9:30 AM  NRC  TIME: APPROX 9:45 AM  INCIDENT NUMBER: 599099 NANCY BENNET  KANSAS EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT, FOLLOWING THE NRC CALL, INCIDENT NUMBER 1004020830SM, SIEVI MURRAY  KANSAS DEPARTMENT OF AGRICULTURE, FOLLOWING THE NRC CALL, ROXY IN TOPEKA

THE TRACTOR'S LEFT SIDE WAS OFF THE GROUND, WITH LEFT REAR AXLE ABOUT 4 TO 5 FEET OFF THE GROUND. PHIL KUYVENHOVEN BILL GULICK ASHLEY TRANSPORT ARRIVED AT SCENE LISA WITH EMA (EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT ASSOC) ARRIVED NEXT IDEM WAS CONTACTED. ABOUT 4000 GALLONS WERE PUMPED OFF TRAILER TO ANOTHER TRAILER ASSISTED BY MARK AT KOCH MATERIALS (SHIPPER) SOME EMULSION HAD LEAKED THRU TO NOTCH AT TIME OF ACCIDENT, UNKNOWN YET AS TO AMOUNT. FIREMAN, OFFICERS, BILL STUFFLEBEAM AND MARK (KOCH) WORKED ON GETTING THE EMULSION OUT OF THE TRAILER AND ON TO THE ROAD, AS THIS IS WHAT THE EMULSION IS USED FOR TO PUT ON GRAVEL ROADS TO CONTROL THE DUST. DUE TO THE LEAKAGE ON THE GROUND (DITCH AREA) EMS WAS CONTACTED.
